post_text:
Here’s what big ph*rm@ doesn’t want you to know…

Mushrooms are revolutionizing modern medicine!

From boosting immunity to sharpening your mind, these versatile fungi offer a bounty of health benefits that are hard to ignore.

What really makes them game changers are these key ingredients:

- Polysaccharides - complex sugars that stimulate the immune system and have been shown to have anti-inflammatory and antioxidant effects.
- Beta-glucans - type of soluble fiber that helps regulate the immune system by binding to immune cells and stimulate them to attack invading pathogens, while also reducing inflammation in the body.
- Active hexose correlated compound - nutritional product extracted from a variety of mushrooms that is commonly used to prevent and treat cancer. It contains a mixture of the polysaccharides, amino acids and minerals.

I have experienced the amazing benefits first hand.

My go-tos are @real_mushrooms and @thegeniusbrand.

For more on mushrooms, drop the words “Mushroom guide” for my FREE in depth guide on the subject

Have you also had an amazing experience with using mushrooms?

#medicinalmushroom #fungi #fungilove #mushroomlove #mushroom #mushrooms

Apparently Gliophorus viridis can vary from pale, through teal green. This is definitely at the teal end of the scale. I was a very happy photographer when I spotted these in a wee mossy knoll!

🆔 Gliophorus viridis 
📍 Mokaihaha Ecological Reserve 
🗓️ 7 May 2024 
📷 Olympus E-M5 Mkii
🔬 M.Zuiko 30mm f3.5 macro

🆔 𝘔𝘺𝘤𝘦𝘯𝘢 𝘪𝘯𝘵𝘦𝘳𝘳𝘶𝘱𝘵𝘢 

🌐 Arnold Dam, Moana,  New Zealand 

⏰ 5th June 2024

Possibly the best 𝘔𝘺𝘤𝘦𝘯𝘢 𝘪𝘯𝘵𝘦𝘳𝘳𝘶𝘱𝘵𝘢 shot Inhaber ever taken. Thanks to this nice cluster Nadine Campbell and I found conveniently located at the entrance of Arnold Dam Track. I thought it was purposely left at the side of the track from @kiwichickjo, but turns out it might be the works of Mother Nature itself.

A gift 🎁 from the forest to hardworking fungi photographers, I guess 😂😁
--------------------------------------------

🌐 Arnold Dam, Moana,  New Zealand 

⏰ 1st June 2024

post_text:
🍄 🥰 🍄 🐛 🍄 🐌 🍄

🆔 𝘌𝘯𝘵𝘰𝘭𝘰𝘮𝘢 𝘩𝘰𝘤𝘩𝘴𝘵𝘦𝘵𝘵𝘦𝘳𝘪

🌐 Arnold Dam, Moana,  New Zealand 

⏰ 9th May 2024

Not much happening in the West Coast, the forest condition is relatively dry comparing to the last two visits I have made since Easter weekend.

Once again, these two shots are a set of good example once again illustrating the magic of focus stacking. Through selecting the number of shots to create a photo, you can manipulate the background of the photo, whether you like a bokeh sort of blur or the background that has all the details.

From this post onwards, I will also try to take a video clip to show the surrounding of the mushroom and possibly let you have the idea of the actual size of the mushroom featured in my individual post.

--------------------------------------------

Not much happening in the West Coast, the forest condition is relatively dry comparing to the last two visits I have made since Easter weekend.

Once again, these two shots are a set of good example once again illustrating the magic of focus stacking. Through selecting the number of shots to create a photo, you can manipulate the background of the photo, whether you like a bokeh sort of blur or the background that has all the details.

post_text:
Nature is, once again, the MVP.⁠
⁠
Scientists have found an ocean-borne fungus chomping through plastic trash suspended in the mega-sized garbage patch in the Pacific Ocean.⁠
⁠
The fungus, named Parengyodontium album, can break down UV-exposed polyethylene, the most pervasive form of plastic waste in our oceans.⁠
⁠
It's exciting news, but it doesn't mean you can start recklessly going through plastic grocery bags and water bottles. Our new hero can break down a piece of plastic at roughly 0.05 percent per day.⁠
⁠
It is, however, a reminder of how impressive the world's species are.⁠
⁠
Read more about plastic-eating fungi at the link in our bio.
IG_auto_desc: Photo by Futurism on June 05, 2024. May be an image of text that says 'SCIENTISTS FIND PLASTIC-EATING PLASTIC -EATING FUNGUS FEASTING ON GREAT PACIFIC GARBAGE PATCH Futurism'.

post_text:
☘️🧘‍♀️NADA SE VA DE TU VIDA🧘‍♀️☘️

🌞Nada se va de tu vida...
Hasta que hayas aprendido, lo que necesitabas saber...

🌞No es el tiempo el que cura las heridas...
Eres tú quién se cura a sí mismo(a), a través del tiempo...

🌞La esperanza, es desear que algo suceda...
La fe, es creer que va a suceder...
Y la valentía, es hacer que suceda...

🌞Nunca olvides, qué las palabras
son livianas como el viento...
Pero tienen un poder tan grande como el universo...
Qué con una palabra se puede vivir...
Y por una palabra, se puede morir...

🌞Los que con el alma se aman...
Sólo con el alma se hablan...

🌞La verdadera grandeza de una persona, no es aquello que alcanza...
Sino aquello que supera...

🌞Siente el pensamiento...
Piensa el sentimiento...

🌞Nunca se puede cometer
el mismo error dos veces...
Porque la segunda vez, no es un error, es una elección...

🌞Cómo aprender a soltar lo que te hace daño, si te aferras a cargarlo?
Abre las manos y deja que caiga por su propio peso...

🌞Los encuentros más importantes, ya han sido planeados por las almas, antes incluso, que los cuerpos se hayan visto nunca...

🌞Camina a tu ritmo, no te apresures...
Qué al único lugar donde tienes que llegar, es a ti mísmo(a)...

🌞No existe mejor pregunta que una mirada...
Ni mejor respuesta que una sonrísa...

🌞El tiempo que tarda un problema en irse de tu vida, es el mismo tiempo que tardas en entender y agradecer, qué sólo ha venido para hacer de tí una mejor persona...

🌞Nadie escoge su amor...
Nadie el momento...
Ni el sitio...
Ni la edad...
Ni la persona...
Deja qué brille tu luz...
Sigue tu instinto...
El universo te abrirá sus puertas...

Decreta para esta nueva semana :

🕉️Hoy elijo soltar con amor, lo que aún no puedo transformar. HECHO ESTÁ, 💜💜💜.

Un abrazo de luz 👁️🦋👁️bendiciones Namaste.

食中毒のリスクがあることを十二分に認識して自己責任で楽しんでいます。種の同定に100％の自信が無いきのこや山菜は食べません。食用とされる天然きのこや山菜であっても体質・体調や食べる量、下処理や調理方法の誤りで中毒を起こすこともあることを留意してください🙏

褐剛毛小菇 𝘔𝘺𝘤𝘦𝘯𝘢 𝘣𝘳𝘶𝘯𝘯𝘦𝘪𝘴𝘦𝘵𝘰𝘴𝘢
- 𝘣𝘳𝘶𝘯𝘯𝘦𝘪𝘴𝘦𝘵𝘰𝘴𝘢 means “brown-bristle”
- 𝘔. 𝘣𝘳𝘶𝘯𝘯𝘦𝘪𝘴𝘦𝘵𝘰𝘴𝘢 is characterized by having bright orange pileus with long pileosetae, the hairy stipe rising from the basal disc.
- It’s a common species in the low-altitude mountainous part of Taiwan.
. 
.

post_text:
Um cogumelo "funil" solitário crescendo no solo em mata de araucária.

Vi que parecia ser do gênero Panus, e lá no iNaturalist o @deniis_zaba sugeriu que pode ser da espécie Panus capelariae.

Procurando mais informações pela internet vi que essa é uma espécie descrita recentemente por pesquisadores aqui do Brasil.

📸 Registro feito em 30/05/24.

post_text:
Here’s what big ph*rm@ doesn’t want you to know…

Mushrooms are revolutionizing modern medicine!

From boosting immunity to sharpening your mind, these versatile fungi offer a bounty of health benefits that are hard to ignore.

What really makes them game changers are these key ingredients:

- Polysaccharides - complex sugars that stimulate the immune system and have been shown to have anti-inflammatory and antioxidant effects.
- Beta-glucans - type of soluble fiber that helps regulate the immune system by binding to immune cells and stimulate them to attack invading pathogens, while also reducing inflammation in the body.
- Active hexose correlated compound - nutritional product extracted from a variety of mushrooms that is commonly used to prevent and treat cancer. It contains a mixture of the polysaccharides, amino acids and minerals.

I have experienced the amazing benefits first hand.

My go-tos are @real_mushrooms and @thegeniusbrand.

For more on mushrooms, drop the words “Mushroom guide” for my FREE in depth guide on the subject

Have you also had an amazing experience with using mushrooms?

post_text:
ℹ️ Dünnsporiges Kranzbecherchen (Vibrissea flavorirens)

Vibrissea flavorirens ist ein Bewohner sauberer Bäche, Quellsümpfe usw. Es besiedelt, oft sehr zahlreich, entrindete, harte Laubholzäste, die ständig von fließendem Wasser umspült werden. Die Apothecien werden ca 2-3mm groß, sind kurz gestielt und haben einen charakteristischen, zahnradähnlich gekerbten Rand.

Die dünnen Fäden, die auf dem letzten Bild im Hintergrund herumfliegen, sind die, mit bis 250μm Länge, riesigen Sporen. 

🗓️ 26.05.2024
🍴  ungenießbar

post_text:
Con esta maravillosa especie (Atheniella adonis) y la manifestación más linda que he visto de ellas hasta ahora, les dejo el afiche de nuestra expedición fotográfica "Costa fúngica del Maule", la cual se realizará los días 14, 15, y 16 de Junio. 
Así es, serán 3 días de exploración intensiva en busca de toda la biodiversidad posible, pero por supuesto con enfoque especial en el mítico Reino Fungi y sus extravagantes y magníficos representantes.😍🍄

Además, podrás aprender todos los secretos para lograr mejores fotografías, a través de la experiencia. 

Cualquier consulta, me escriben o comentan, o bien, a contacto@biodiversidadchilena.cl 🙌🏾

Pd: Si sé, la especie del afiche no corresponde al reino fungi, porque es un Myxomyceto, pero es parte del micromundo que descubriremos durante la expedición 😎😱🤯

Además, podrás aprender todos los secretos para lograr mejores fotografías, a través de la experiencia. 

Cualquier consulta, me escriben o comentan, o bien, a contacto@biodiversidadchilena.cl 🙌🏾

Pd: Si sé, la especie del afiche no corresponde al reino fungi, porque es un Myxomyceto, pero es parte del micromundo que descubriremos durante la expedición 😎😱🤯

褐剛毛小菇 𝘔𝘺𝘤𝘦𝘯𝘢 𝘣𝘳𝘶𝘯𝘯𝘦𝘪𝘴𝘦𝘵𝘰𝘴𝘢
- 𝘣𝘳𝘶𝘯𝘯𝘦𝘪𝘴𝘦𝘵𝘰𝘴𝘢 means “brown-bristle”
- 𝘔. 𝘣𝘳𝘶𝘯𝘯𝘦𝘪𝘴𝘦𝘵𝘰𝘴𝘢 is characterized by having bright orange pileus with long pileosetae, the hairy stipe rising from the basal disc.
- It’s a common species in the low-altitude mountainous part of Taiwan.
. 
.

⚠️天然食材を食べることは…
食中毒のリスクがあることを十二分に認識して自己責任で楽しんでいます。種の同定に100％の自信が無いきのこや山菜は食べません。食用とされる天然きのこや山菜であっても体質・体調や食べる量、下処理や調理方法の誤りで中毒を起こすこともあることを留意してください🙏

post_text:
Peek-a-BLUE! For #Wee#Wed today, here are some Mycena interrupta, common name Pixie’s Parasol, which was very high on my list of fungi to find and photograph during my trip to Australia and New Zealand, and I was happy to see many!  I was told they are a deeper blue in Australia, but these blue beauties were found in New Zealand.  Aren’t they gorgeous!!!!

The caps are stunning, and so are the gills and base of the mushroom  The second photo shows the gills, and also some of the baby blues, so precious.  What I love most about these, though, is the blue basal disc, which you can see in the closeup in the third figure.  So BLUE!
IG_auto_desc: Photo by Alison Pollack on May 22, 2024. May be an image of mushroom and text that says 'AlisonPollack Alison Pollack'.

post_text:
𝘔𝘺𝘤𝘦𝘯𝘢 𝘪𝘯𝘵𝘦𝘳𝘳𝘶𝘱𝘵𝘢 + scale shots! Another amazing species ticked off my Fungi bucket list. 

One of 12 observations in my part of the country for this mushroom, although they are reasonably common further south. These were found fruiting on a fallen log, presumably 𝘒𝘶𝘯𝘻𝘦𝘢 sp, only managed to find one mature fruiting body, along with plenty of cute fuzzy little nubbins. 

Being too high off the ground for my tripod and awkwardly placed over a small drainage stream, these are handheld focus stacks of 124 and 80 images. 

📸 @omsystem.cameras OMD EM1 Mark III
🔍 M.Zuiko 60mm + Raynox DCR250 & 26mm Extension Tubes
🔦 @godox_global V350o
💡 @cygnustech Diffuser
📚 Focus stacked images

post_text:
純黃竹蓀 𝘗𝘩𝘢𝘭𝘭𝘶𝘴 𝘭𝘶𝘵𝘦𝘶𝘴
- 𝘭𝘶𝘵𝘦𝘶𝘴 means “yellow”
- It clearly differs from 𝘗. 𝘪𝘯𝘥𝘶𝘴𝘪𝘢𝘵𝘶𝘴 in its yellow pileus and indusium.
- 𝘗. 𝘮𝘶𝘭𝘵𝘪𝘤𝘰𝘭𝘰𝘳 is also distinguishable from 𝘗. 𝘭𝘶𝘵𝘦𝘶𝘴 by its orange, pink to red pileus and indusium, and not extended to the ground.

. 
.

post_text: I affectionately call these "Carrots". Buried to the pileus in burnt out earth. @bellyoftheworldmushrooms magic-ed them out of the ground with his trusty knife and discovered their weirdo nether regions. Phaeocollybia perhaps? I've dehydrated these as kinda cool. But sitting on my kitchen table. Shall get to the Herbarium one day.....I kind of want to make one into an earring, so dm me if you have skillz in resin jewellery. D'Aguilar National Park, Queensland, Australia. #fungi #fungiidentification #fungifanatic #fungiphotography #tg6

post_text:
褐剛毛小菇 𝘔𝘺𝘤𝘦𝘯𝘢 𝘣𝘳𝘶𝘯𝘯𝘦𝘪𝘴𝘦𝘵𝘰𝘴𝘢
- 𝘣𝘳𝘶𝘯𝘯𝘦𝘪𝘴𝘦𝘵𝘰𝘴𝘢 means “brown-bristle”
- 𝘔. 𝘣𝘳𝘶𝘯𝘯𝘦𝘪𝘴𝘦𝘵𝘰𝘴𝘢 is characterized by having bright orange pileus with long pileosetae, the hairy stipe rising from the basal disc.
- It’s a common species in the low-altitude mountainous part of Taiwan.
. 
.

post_text:
Um cogumelo "funil" solitário crescendo no solo em mata de araucária.

Vi que parecia ser do gênero Panus, e lá no iNaturalist o @deniis_zaba sugeriu que pode ser da espécie Panus capelariae.

Procurando mais informações pela internet vi que essa é uma espécie descrita recentemente por pesquisadores aqui do Brasil.

📸 Registro feito em 30/05/24.

post_text:
ℹ️ Dünnsporiges Kranzbecherchen (Vibrissea flavorirens)

Vibrissea flavorirens ist ein Bewohner sauberer Bäche, Quellsümpfe usw. Es besiedelt, oft sehr zahlreich, entrindete, harte Laubholzäste, die ständig von fließendem Wasser umspült werden. Die Apothecien werden ca 2-3mm groß, sind kurz gestielt und haben einen charakteristischen, zahnradähnlich gekerbten Rand.

Die dünnen Fäden, die auf dem letzten Bild im Hintergrund herumfliegen, sind die, mit bis 250μm Länge, riesigen Sporen. 

🗓️ 26.05.2024
🍴  ungenießbar

post_text:
Sigan su instagram @ange.s_silva

 𝗠𝘆𝗰𝗲𝗻𝗮 𝗵𝗮𝗲𝗺𝗮𝘁𝗼𝗽𝘂𝘀 🍄.
 
Díganme que no soy la única que ama a la mycena haematopus, pero es que miren esas lamelas 😍🥹❤️.

Cuando voy al bosque suelo sentarme a observar ,así puedo ver bien a mi alrededor, no tengo la certeza con lo que me voy a encontrar aunque el bosque siempre me sorprende, me incita a seguir explorando este fascinante y poco conocido mundo, como este honguito, que a mi me encanta por su color,textura y sus lamelas.
Hoy te dejo información y fotografias de este maravilloso hongo 🍄

𝗜𝗻𝗳𝗼𝗿𝗺𝗮𝗰𝗶𝗼𝗻

 ▶︎ Mycena haematopus pertenece a la familia mycenaceae ,es cosmopolita encontrándose desde el centro al sur austral de Chile.
Su hábitat se encuentra entre el humus húmedo en tocones de madera (descomposicion) y sobre la corteza de arboles vivos dentro del bosque.
Se caracteriza por su látex rojo al dañarse o romperse.
Su sombrero es de color rojo o rosado en la juventud , tornándose rojo marrón al madurar ,su contextura es  frágil y delicada ,como gran parte del género de las denominadas mycenas.

post_text:
Ya están arriba las inscripciones para las talleres  y salidas a terreno de Festival Reino Fungi! 🍄 

Para inscríbete entra a nuestra web www.festivalreinofungi.cl 👉 link en el perfil 👈

Los cupos pueden ser suficientes si como el micelio actuamos en red, considerando a los demás. Priorizando lo que nos robe el corazón y soltando lo que nos encanta, pero estamos dispuestos a dejar para que otro pueda disfrutarlo también.

Recuerden que las demás actividades son gratis y por orden de llegada. 

Nos vemos este 12-13-14 de mayo en Pucón 🙌🏼 ¡ALEGRIA ALEGRIA!🙌🏼

📷 @saraundurraga

post_text:
Fairy library shadowboxes! 🧚‍♀️🍄‍🟫 Overflowing with lovingly handmade miniatures :) 

Each one of these mini wall hangings feature tiny wood shelves, mini fungi sculpture displays, glass bottles of magical ingredients with carefully hand drawn paper labels, acorn cap bowls full of ink-dyed salts, miniature books made from upcycled leather & cardboard scraps that are hand painted with acrylics and metallic ink, little keys, crystal balls, candles, watercolor paper scrolls with twine ties, clay ladybugs, and hand illustrated paper posters! 

I only have one of these pieces left, the crystal collector's library on the 5th slide with natural quartz points found by my local mineral club! 

•

post_text:
We are SOOPA excited to have @noelbadgespugh art featured in our second annual HAWAII MUSHROOM FESTIVAL flyer design 🌈🎨🍄

Save the date:  April 15-16 at Starseed Ranch ⭐️ Join us to celebrate all things MUSHROOMS at the 26 acre off-grid permaculture estate @starseedranch 🌴💙👩🏽‍🌾

A Keiki to kupuna friendly 2-day event devoted to local mushroom education, community + celebration. It will be teeming with talks and hands-on workshops by Hawai'i's leading mycologist, educators, and cultivators.

The fest has something of interest for everyone ranging from the absolute beginner to the seasoned mycologist. 

There is also an emphasis on creative expression in the arts in our mushroom art show, costume contest + display parade, and poetry / theater night! 🎭

Tickets are available now via eventbrite - check it out for more info on what to expect 🎟️ 🔗 LINK IN BIO!
IG_auto_desc: Photo shared by Mālama Mushrooms on January 26, 2023 tagging @noelbadgespugh, @starseedranch, and @hipaghawaii.

This might be my new favorite thing I've ever drawn.😍 You'll get to see the full illustration tomorrow. Until then, enjoy the details! 

Info for the digital art nerds: this entire illustration was done with a set of illustrator brushes I made strictly for this illustration! I'm quite proud of myself. ☺️

post_text:
You're so golden! 💛

The Golden-scruffy Collybia (Cyptotrama asprata) is found all around the world. In Australia it's primarily found along the east coast.

With a cushion-shaped mushroom cap that grows up to 2.7 centimetres in diameter, it's covered in bright yellow and orange protrusions that lose their vibrancy as the mushroom ages.

It's a saprobic fungus, so it processes dead and decaying wood from deciduous and coniferous trees. 🌲 

📸 | Byteme via @inaturalistorg / Atlas of Living Australia

post_text:
The brightly-coloured waxcaps are often thought of as the orchids of the fungi kingdom because they are so vibrant and showy, and also quite particular.  They will only grow on undisturbed, nutrient-poor grasslands like ancient pasture and other land that has never been ploughed or fertilised. As a result, many species are rare and hard to find but some grow much closer to home – literally. 

Waxcaps can appear in garden lawns, grassy churchyards and even the occasional cricket pitch as long as the conditions are right.  Wherever you find them, their presence means you’re in a very special place.

Scarlet Waxcap © Graeme Lyons

post_text:
.
🍄 Wrinkled Peach Mushroom 💦
There is no doubt that there are things that I’m missing from the UK. Autumn and Fungi season is definitely one of them. Over the last couple of weeks my good friend Jamie (@this_forest_floor) has been sending me picture, video and even a Skype updates on the patch of red listed, endangered mushies that we shot last year. Like clockwork, exactly a year later, they are emerging in-spite of some of the harshest droughts in London’s history. 

Im so pleased that Jamie has had the chance to document their growth again this year but it is a shame that I’ve not been able to join in to watch ‘our babies’ (as she called them) grow. Jamie’s love for all things fungi and slime was what started me taking a keen interest into this amazing world. After speaking with Jamie over the last few weeks and watching her spread her fungi love on an interview with @omsystem.cameras yesterday (go watch on YouTube), it has made me pine for all the weird and wonderful fungus that is really lacking where I am in Oz due to it being so dry. 

I still had a few images from these days out that I’d never released, so it seems like a perfect time to post one now as a little love letter to all things mushroom and as a thank you to the Sloog Queen herself for igniting this passion in me last year, taking me on so many awesome forest walks and showing me many incredible species. Thanks Legend 🙏❤️🍄.

post_text:
🍄 🥰 🍄 🐛 🍄 🐌 🍄

🆔 𝘔𝘺𝘤𝘦𝘯𝘢 𝘴𝘶𝘣𝘷𝘪𝘴𝘤𝘰𝘴𝘢

🌐 Pine Valley Track, Blenheim,  New Zealand 

⏰ 12th May 2024

After a rather disappointing day foray in St Arnaud, we were blessed by this amazing foray the following day. Thanks for @kiwichickjo, my first visit to this hidden spot is jawdropping. It's amazing how the surrounding areas of Pine Valley are so arid but yet this valley manage to retain the moisture 💦 in it's forest floor 🍂🍃, thus a wide variety of mushrooms are in abundance 🍄.

I have seen a lot of 𝘔𝘺𝘤𝘦𝘯𝘢 𝘴𝘶𝘣𝘷𝘪𝘴𝘤𝘰𝘴𝘢, but never before a huge colony of this scale. There must be hundreds (even thousand) of individuals growing on this fallen log. Seeing them was a bit of serendipitous, @kiwichickjo was waiting for me photographing an 𝘈𝘮𝘢𝘯𝘪𝘵𝘢 𝘢𝘶𝘴𝘵𝘳𝘢𝘭𝘪𝘴 and head into the bush to look for more subject matters, and Shazam she found this for us.

Swipe 👈🏻 to see the video I got for the whole colony.

post_text:
Con esta maravillosa especie (Atheniella adonis) y la manifestación más linda que he visto de ellas hasta ahora, les dejo el afiche de nuestra expedición fotográfica "Costa fúngica del Maule", la cual se realizará los días 14, 15, y 16 de Junio. 
Así es, serán 3 días de exploración intensiva en busca de toda la biodiversidad posible, pero por supuesto con enfoque especial en el mítico Reino Fungi y sus extravagantes y magníficos representantes.😍🍄

Además, podrás aprender todos los secretos para lograr mejores fotografías, a través de la experiencia. 

Cualquier consulta, me escriben o comentan, o bien, a contacto@biodiversidadchilena.cl 🙌🏾

Pd: Si sé, la especie del afiche no corresponde al reino fungi, porque es un Myxomyceto, pero es parte del micromundo que descubriremos durante la expedición 😎😱🤯

post_text:
🆔 𝘌𝘯𝘵𝘰𝘭𝘰𝘮𝘢 𝘮𝘦𝘭𝘢𝘯𝘰𝘤𝘦𝘱𝘩𝘢𝘭𝘶𝘮

🌐  Mt Fyffe Forest Walk, Kaikoura,  New Zealand 

⏰ 3rd April 2024

True black beauty...😍

From the top, it looked like an aged, dried-out mushroom. But underneath that charcoal black cap, the gills are simply astounding. The white gills with dark edge and the black cap, the contrast of these colors just made 𝘌𝘯𝘵𝘰𝘭𝘰𝘮𝘢 𝘮𝘦𝘭𝘢𝘯𝘰𝘤𝘦𝘱𝘩𝘢𝘭𝘶𝘮 such a magnificent mushroom which can be deceiving under the eyes of typical passerbys.

--------------------------------------------

📷 Olympus OMD EM1 MarkIII 
🔭 Zuiko 60mm Macro
⚙️ 1.5 sec, F2.8
📚 35 photos stacked with Helicon Focus Pro

🌐 Arnold Dam, Moana,  New Zealand 

⏰ 9th May 2024

Not much happening in the West Coast, the forest condition is relatively dry comparing to the last two visits I have made since Easter weekend.

Once again, these two shots are a set of good example once again illustrating the magic of focus stacking. Through selecting the number of shots to create a photo, you can manipulate the background of the photo, whether you like a bokeh sort of blur or the background that has all the details.

From this post onwards, I will also try to take a video clip to show the surrounding of the mushroom and possibly let you have the idea of the actual size of the mushroom featured in my individual post.

post_text:
#SanValentino è sinonimo di baci, cioccolatini ma soprattutto… #fiori!

Immancabili le #rose, simbolo di #passione per eccellenza. Ma vale la pena fare regalarle alla persona amata? La risposta – nella maggior parte dei casi – è no. O almeno se si vuole fare un bel regalo all’#ambiente.

In vista di questa celebrazione, infatti, tonnellate di rose refrigerate vengono trasportate da Paesi del Sud America e dell’Africa orientale all’Europa, dove vengono poi vendute spesso a caro prezzo. Ma dietro la bellezza di questi fiori si nascondono veri e propri cocktail di #pesticidi, comprese quelle certificate Fairtrade. A svelare il lato oscuro delle rose è la recente analisi condotta dalla rivista tedesca Öko-Test.

In totale sono stati 21 i #mazzidirose esaminati, venduti da note aziende leader nella consegna dei fiori come Fleurop e Euroflorist. E il numero di diversi pesticidi rilevati è impressionante: ben 54. Oltre 3/4 dei boquet hanno riportato dei punteggi scarsi o insufficienti, inclusi quelli molto costosi. I prezzi sono molto variabili: vanno da 1,99 euro per dodici rose a 39,95 euro per otto rose.

Fra le sostanze rilevate vi sono anche fitofarmaci potenzialmente cancerogeni, mutageni, reprotossici e tossici per le api. Ma non finisce qua. Su 3/4 dei mezzi di fiori analizzati è stato spruzzato uno spray a base di #insetticida Thiacloprid e di #fungicida Carbendazim, messi al bando in Europa. Secondo l’Agenzia europea per le sostanze chimiche (ECHA), questa sostanze sono potenzialmente cangerogene e possono influenzare la fertilità e provocare danni nei nascituri.

Quando si parla di rose, c’è un altro fattore da considerare oltre alla spinosa questione dei pesticidi: ovvero lo #sfruttamentodeilavoratori. Nella maggior parte dei casi le rose arrivano da Paesi africani come il Kenya, fino al 70% di quelli presenti sul mercato europeo. Qui migliaia di lavoratori sono costretti a turni pesanti per paghe da fame e le donne, in molti casi, sono vittime di molestie sessuali.

Gran parte delle rose vendute negli Usa e in Europa arriva anche dalla Colombia e dall’Ecuador, Paesi in cui lo sfruttamento minorile è molto radicato. 
. 
. 
#greenme #greenmeitalia

post_text:
Cientistas da Universidade Estadual do Ceará (Uece) criaram um fungicida natural capaz de proteger mais de 500 espécies de plantas, como cajueiro, coqueiro e pé de acerola, contra doenças como a podridão seca (causada pelo Lasiodiplodia theobromae). A descoberta recebeu carta-patente do Instituto Nacional da Propriedade Industrial (INPI).

Os próximos passos dos pesquisadores serão para comercializar o produto e para realizar outros testes na avaliação do uso farmacológico da substância. As informações foram divulgadas pela comunicação da Universidade.

O fungicida pode proteger plantações inteiras, com baixo custo e de forma natural, o que pode beneficiar muitos que dependem da agricultura familiar para o sustento. Além disso, há possibilidade de uso como medicamento para humanos conforme o estudo avance.

Veja mais detalhes em nosso site, acessando o link que está na bio. (Foto: Uece/Reprodução) #fungicida #ciencia #Ceará #DiáriodoNordeste

post_text:
Fungicida natural e eficaz para tomates 🍅
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Hoje partilho uma receita de fungicida natural simples de preparar em casa e que pode ser útil para prevenir ou tratar as doenças fúngicas mais comuns desta planta, como é o caso do oídio e míldio.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
𝗣𝗮𝗿𝗮 𝗽𝗿𝗲𝘃𝗲𝗻𝗰̧𝗮̃𝗼:
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Preparação: Fazer regas com leite diluído: 3 copos de leite para 7 copos de água. 
Aplicação: Deve ser aplicado de manhã, regando uma a duas vezes por semana.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
𝗣𝗮𝗿𝗮 𝘁𝗿𝗮𝘁𝗮𝗺𝗲𝗻𝘁𝗼:
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
Preparação: Diluir 1 copo de leite em 4 copos de água. Agitar a mistura e pulverizar. 
Aplicação: Aplicar duas vezes por semana se as folhas já estiverem com sintomas evidentes de oídio.
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀
❗️Não esqueçam que o ideal será realizar as pulverizações, preferencialmente de forma preventiva, quando as condições climáticas forem favoráveis ao aparecimento de doenças. Após o seu estabelecimento, a maioria das doenças é complicada de controlar ou pode nem ser controlada.
.
.
.

post_text:
Finalmente aderi ao queridinho das “blogueres de casa” 🤣

O #lysoform Bruto Original (têm outros tipos tbm) é um desinfetante de uso geral, funcionando como: #germicida #bactericida #fungicida.
.
.
.
.

Esse produto é indicado para uso em limpeza de latas, lixeiras, pias e ralos, uma vez que possui capacidade de eliminar bactérias e germes. Dessa forma a limpeza é feita de forma que o mau cheiro seja eliminado e o ambiente limpo, esse tipo de produto não pode entrar em contato com o corpo humano.
.
.

Ele também pode ser usado na limpeza de ambientes e superfícies laváveis como pisos e azulejos, podendo ser aplicado também nas paredes internas e bordas do vaso sanitário.
Outra opção de uso de produto é na limpeza das roupas, usando apenas durante o enxague. .
.
Quando usado na forma pura o produto age como bactericida, podendo ser usado para desinfetar paredes, armários, maçanetas, entre outras coisas que não são levadas à boca.

O indicado é aplicar e deixar agir por dez minutos, outra dica é colocar o produto em uma pequena área do local que deseja aplicar para se certificar de que não irá causar manchas ou danificar o objeto ou local.
.
.

Um alerta do fabricante é que esse produto não pode ser usado por mulheres grávidas 🤰🏻, pois ele possui em sua fórmula o benzeno, substância que pode ocasionar algum tipo de má formação no feto.

MODO DE USO:
.
.

Para desodorização diluir um copo (250 Ml) em 10 litros de água.
Para lavar roupas use ½ copo (125 Ml) no processo final da lavagem. Não precisa enxaguar.

Para desinfecção use o produto puro.
Tempo de contato: 10 Minutos.
.
.
Tbm pode ser usado na limpeza de estofado, colchão; para facilitar o uso nesses casos coloque dentro de um borrifador. Essa dica aqui aprendi com a Rê @duplex401 👍🏼
.
.
.

post_text:
Amanita muscaria, Fly Agaric, Amanitaceae. An introduced species to Australia, it is mycorrhizal with northern hemisphere conifers and hardwoods.

 Autumn and winter is when A. muscaria dominates the pine forests of Australia, though after the amount of rainfall we have had this summer, it’s not unusual to have them popping up now, in the same way Lactarius deliciosus (saffron milk cap) has been plentiful this summer. I was puzzled when I found this, as it was in the middle of a Eucalyptus forest, though after looking around I found two Pinus radiata growing a little way away. 

 Known around the world for a variety of reasons, it has been portrayed in folklore, prepared in the kitchen for food, as medicine, and as a hallucinogen (it contains ibotenic acid, a neurotoxin which converts to muscimol, a psychoactive compound, once digested). 

 Amanita muscaria poses a serious threat to the biodiversity of native fungi in the Myrtle Beech forests of Victoria and Tasmania, where it has formed Mycohrriza with Nothofagus cunninghamii.

It’s easy to see why they are called swamp beacon. Though they usually grow in dark areas and are rather small, you can easily spot them because of their colour.
Mitrula elegans - this miniature beacon is growing on decaying leaves in wetlands and is saprobic, it decomposes wood and leaf litter.
Found these a few days ago.

One thing I love about Instagram is being able to follow people like Kate @garden_and_cosmos who lives on the other side of the planet from me. She shares all the incredible nature she explores. The nature in Australia is so stunning. Her photos inspire me and she generously shares some of her fungi photos with me to use in my artwork. Thank you Kate!!!! 

These gorgeous fungi are Anthrocophyllum archeri aka Orange Fan Fungus and Crepidotis stramaticus. You can see the original images on her feed.

These gorgeous fungi are Anthrocophyllum archeri aka Orange Fan Fungus and Crepidotis stramaticus. You can see the original images on her feed.

post_text:
🍄 This month the Spiritual Ecology Study Club gathers once again. Priya Subberwal leads a community discussion around fungal associates. If you’re a lover of mushrooms, and like us, find much fertile ground for learning and turning from fungal metaphors, join us on the session this week by becoming an advaya member (unlock this with a 7-day free trial!) 

Taking a leaf out of Anna Tsing’s book (somewhat literally), we will think with a politics of impurity and contamination, via our encounters. If we all carry a history of contamination, and purity is not an option, how do we make and re-make the world? What do fungal associates teach us in this respect, about radical movement building, non-linearity, decentralisation and emergence?
IG_auto_desc: Photo shared by advaya | your home for transformative learning on November 13, 2023 tagging @liminal_soup.

post_text:
At the nature reserve Björnö, Kalmar, SE Sweden you find one of the largest population of old oaks (Quercus robur). One thing making them valuble to insects are the colonizing fungi species. Softening the wood and fill it with tasty mycelia for different larva. One species like old dry oak branches: The Oak Mazegill (Daedalia quercina, korkmussling). 
.
.
.
.

post_text:
BLUE OR GREEN OR SOMETHING IN BETWEEN? 
.
Not all fungi has stems and gills. This Ascomycetes variety is known as Chlorociboria aeruginascens, and comes in amazingly vibrant colours. One thing I love about it, is that it can stain the wood it grows on, filling the forest with tiny smurf logs.
.
These lil discs are about 3-4mm across. But what colour would you say these are? 
.
Nikon D780
Sigma 105mm f2.8 Macro
.
.
.
.

post_text:
TRACK-SIDE TREATS
.
Lately I've been venturing off track in search of new specimens and species. But last Friday I had to be slightly less* intrepid as I was accompanied by my lovely wife, on a stroll of the waterfall circuit of Mount Field National Park.
.
Turns out I didn't need to enter the lair of the leeches, as this gorgeous Chlorociboria aeruginascens cluster was conveniently positioned right on the side of the track. Jackpot!
.
Love these blue green gems. A week or so ago I posted a snap of these and the concensus was that they were emerald or jade in colour (among other suggestions). I haven't played with the colour of these at all, and this time I'm seeing much more blue in the caps. Nature amirite?
.
*we did go off track once to explore the second tier of Russell Falls. Fun times.
.
Nikon D780
Sigma 105mm f2.8 Macro
.
.
.

post_text:
WHAT EVEN ARE YA?
.
I found this pinkish beauties on some peeling bark. Quite by accident in fact. I stumbled over a mossy rock and there they were. 
.
Flicking through my Tasmanian Fungi Field Guide, I can't be sure exactly what it is. My best guess is Crepidotus variabilis, but these were much pinker and larger than other specimens I've found. And it was on bark, not a stick?
.
🤔 Would welcome any expert advice. 
.
Nikon D780
Sigma 105mm f2.8 Macro
.
.
.
.

post_text:
I’m pretty fascinated by this Polaskia chichipe cutting. This species grows a lot like myrtillocactus: tree-like with many branches growing outward at the top. The cut wasn’t drying well so I put some sulfur powder on it to inhibit fungal growth and the cut hardened.
.

It’s easy to see why they are called swamp beacon. Though they usually grow in dark areas and are rather small, you can easily spot them because of their colour.
Mitrula elegans - this miniature beacon is growing on decaying leaves in wetlands and is saprobic, it decomposes wood and leaf litter.
Found these a few days ago.

post_text:
Fomitopsis betulina
EN
This species is a saprotroph or parasite specific to Betula spp. It can be found on logs, dead trees, but sometimes in live trees too, although it possibly only infects already decaying, trees. 
Like other brown rot fungi it degrades the carbohydrate fraction of lignocellulose but, in contrast to white rot fungi, leaves lignin in the form of cubical brown fragments.
In Portugal I have only found them growing in high altitude in mountainous areas.

PT
Esta espécie é um saprófito ou parasita específico de espécies do género Betula. Pode observar-se em troncos e ramos, árvores mortas, mas por vezes também em espécimes vivos, provavelmente aproveitando árvores já em mau estado fitossanitário em que a infeção é mais fácil de propagar.
Como outros fungos de podridão castanha degrada a parte dos hidratos de carbono(celulose) da lignocelulose, deixando a lignina na forma de fragmentos cúbicos castanhos, em contraste com os fungos de podridão branca que degradam na forma oposta. 
Em Portugal só encontrei esta espécie em habitats de altitude em serras. 

Serra da Arada 05/2024

🧚🏼‍♂️ Gomita del bosque (Guepiniopsis alpina) 

Es un tipo de hongo de color amarillo o anaranjado cuando es joven y rojizo en su etapa adulta. Tiene un cuerpo fructífero o carpóforo pequeño de contextura gelatinosa (juventud) y coriácea (madurez) 🍄🤏

En la fotografía tome una rama caída de madera muerta que estaba en el suelo del bosque del género Nothofagus en @parquetricahue en la región del Maule 🌳🍁🌿🍂 

📍Amplia distribución desde la IV región hasta la Patagonia chilena y Argentina Austral 🏞️🏔️

🍽️ No tiene valor gastronómico

post_text:
"We went into the jungle, there were too many of us; we had too much money, too much equipment and, little by little, we went insane,"

Here's a beautiful mini hoop house of Ganoderma lucidum (Reishi)

Likely in the mountains of China. 

Low tech mushroom cultivation isn't just possible, it's quite ideal. Yet if nothing else, humans are skilled at complicating a simple matter.

If those weird techniques aren't working, try something simpler. Go for the old school approach. Hug the earth and let the mushrooms grow. 

Photo found on the internet without credit to original photographer. Know it? Please drop their info here

So that more people can see this and learn to be a mushroom too:

post_text:
SABÍAS QUÉ?

La melena de león, o Hericium erinaceus, es un hongo que se ha utilizado en la medicina tradicional china y japonesa debido a sus posibles beneficios para la salud. Algunos de los beneficios asociados con la melena de león incluyen:

1. Apoyo cognitivo:
Se ha sugerido que los compuestos en la melena de león pueden mejorar la función cerebral, incluida la memoria y la concentración.

2. Estimulación del crecimiento de nervios:
La melena de león contiene componentes que pueden promover la regeneración de las células nerviosas y ayudar en la salud del sistema nervioso.

3. Propiedades antioxidantes: 
Los antioxidantes en este hongo pueden ayudar a combatir el estrés oxidativo y proteger las células del daño.

4. Refuerzo del sistema inmunológico:
Se ha estudiado si los polisacáridos de la melena de león pueden fortalecer la respuesta inmunológica del cuerpo ante infecciones.

5. Salud digestiva:
Algunos informes sugieren que la melena de león puede beneficiar la salud del sistema digestivo y reducir la inflamación gastrointestinal.

6. Potencial para la salud cardiovascular:
Aunque la investigación está en curso, se ha explorado si la melena de león podría tener un impacto positivo en la salud del corazón y los niveles de colesterol.

El @museodelhongo continúa fructificando y hará su aparición n° 19 🍄 “ MUTUALISTAS ” 🍄en la ciudad de Talca | Desde el 8 al 28 de junio 2022 

Esta imperdible experiencia inmersiva, está inspirada en el abrazo microscópico entre especies vegetales nativas de la región del Maule y sus compañeros los hongos micorrícicos. 

Te invitamos a conocer especies como el ruil, queule y las orquídeas, siendo partícipe de este despliegue colaborativo entre investigación científica, arte
y tecnología. 

¿Dónde? La muestra tendrá lugar en la Universidad Católica del Maule @ucatolicamaule (3 norte #650, Talca), abriendo sus puertas desde el miércoles 8 de junio y estará abierta al público hasta el martes 28 de junio. 

Podrás acceder a la sala en los siguientes días y horarios:
9:00 a 19:00 de lunes a viernes
9:00 a 13:00 sábado
📋se solicitará pase de movilidad

post_text:
A Fungi Nomade Fest 🍄‍🟫 

Last week’s weather was all over the place. From blazing sun and pouring rain, to even hail on the same day! 

Even with harsh weather changes like these, there is one #supercrop that can grow year-round in a controlled indoor environment, and still be incredibly #sustainable 🌱 @ilfungoeclettico 👀‼️

Considering the drastic changes of temperature in one day, we wanted to satisfy both warm and cold cravings ✨

For the zuppa di giorno, @pinasiotto went with a twist on the iconic #Pancotto but with fungi, chives, asparagi, and a generous sprinkle of Parmigiano 💛

I took the lead with a Fungiche, a #plantbased twist on a #PeruvianCeviche 🇵🇪 Slow-cooked #Pleurotus Florida marinated in tomato water, red onion, lemon and orange juice 🍊 For a sweet and smoky taste, we added charred bell peppers, and finished with a celery, ginger, and cilantro “leche de tigre” 🐯

🧆 As a bonus, of course I got to try their Lentil Falafel with a cucumber pico de gallo and smoked eggplant sauce 

Once again, I am so thankful for this empowering hub that continues to encourage me to let go of fears and just have fun(gi) 🤣💜 @cristina_fiorese 

#pastonomade #pastonomadebologna #ilfungoeclettico #urbanmushrooms #urbanfungi #fungigrowing #fungifreaks #vegetariancooking #vegetariancuisine #veganceviche #cevichevegano #cevichevegetariano #fungiculture #fungicultura #pleurotusflorida
IG_auto_desc: Photo shared by Sophie the girl who eaaaats on May 26, 2024 tagging @pastonomade, and @ilfungoeclettico. May be an image of shiitake mushrooms, congee, asparagus and grits.

post_text:
En el bosque existen alimentos de todo orden, alimentos sustanciales en su mayoría son el resultado de procesos que la alquimia natural del bosque lleva a cabo para la existencia de la vida.

Estos alimentos adquiridos de manera natural e incorporados espontáneamente son los responsables establecer determinadas interacciones que favorecen nuestro equilibro orgánico nos permiten experimentar un estado de bienestar integral.

Si te interesa comprender como ocurre esta maravillosa alquimia, no te pierdas esta increíble experiencia  que  estaremos facilitando en el marco del @miceliofest

Les espero el próximo domingo 2 de junio a las 11:30 horas en el parque @borderioparque

post_text:
Happy #SlimeMoldSunday to Myxomycete lovers new and old! These amazing myxo fruiting bodies are Diachea leucopodia, one of my favorites because of their beautiful iridescence.  As with many slime molds, this species changes colors several times during its brief life cycle.  When they first arise from the white plasmodium, the fruiting bodies are white.  They then turn almost black, and as they mature and dry the peridium (outer covering of the spore-containing body) turns into these strikingly beautiful iridescent blue, purple, and brown colors on a white stout stalk.  Although the individual fruiting bodies are tiny, only 1-2mm tall, they can be easy to spot because they grow in dense and large clusters on leaves, grasses, and live and decaying plant material.  To see how tiny they are, see the second photo, which shows a few fruiting bodies on a twig with the tip of a fine point pen for scale.

A little technical info for those of you who might be interested.  To photograph such tiny myxos with sharp detail, I use an extreme macro lens.  With such high magnifications, the depth of field (portion of the subject that is in sharp focus) is less than 0.05mm. To get a photo of the entire fruiting body in focus, I use a technique called focus stacking. My camera is mounted on a finely tuned rail, and the camera is moved in minuscule increments between each photo, so that the focal point changes with each photo.   For this photo, I took 138 individual images, which were then “stacked” with specialized computer software that combines the most in-focus portions of each of the individual images into a composite image that shows everything in focus from front to back.
IG_auto_desc: Photo by Alison Pollack on February 20, 2022.

post_text:
Dendrocollybia racemosa -  Branched shanklet 

Not my find but a collaborative effort to collect and record this rare species. I’m thrilled to get the opportunity to witness this one. 

The location has been recorded, and pending permissions, a sample will be making its way to Kew Gardens to be included in their genome sequencing projects and the national collection.

Found by: Nicky Freeman
Collected & record by: Iona Fraser @ashdownforage

The species is characterised by its unusual stem, which is covered with short lateral branches. The branches often produce spherical slimeheads of translucent conidiophores 
on their swollen tips. The conidiophores produce conidia (asexual spores) by mitosis. Because the fungus can rely on either sexual or asexual modes of reproduction, fruit bodies sometimes have reduced or even missing caps. The unusual stems originate from black pea-sized structures called sclerotia. The anamorphic form of the fungus, known as Tilachlidiopsis racemosa, is missing the sexual stage of its life cycle. It can reproduce at relatively low temperatures, an adaptation believed to improve its ability to grow quickly and fruit on decomposing mushrooms. (Info via Wikimili)
#allthingsfungi
IG_auto_desc: Photo shared by Max Mudie on October 03, 2022 tagging @ashdownforage.

post_text:
Buchen-Milchling, süßlicher Milchling 
Lactarius subdulcis

Gattung:  Milchlinge 

Info/Vorkommen/Standort:
der Symbiosepilz wächst gerne im Laubwald bei Buchen, manchmal auch auf verrottendem Holz oder Baumstrünken

Hut: 
Zimtbraun bis dunkelbraun, Huthaut glatt und ungezont, Hutrand lange eingerollt 

Lamellen:
weißlich bis blassocker, angewachsen, mit Zahn herablaufend, mit Zwischenlamellen

Stiel: 
blass bräunlich bis fleischocker, weißlich striegelig behaftete Myzelbasis

Milch: weißlich, nicht verfärbend

SPP:  hellgelb 

Geruch:  leicht gummiartig, etwas nach Blattwanzen 

Fundort: 📸  Landkreis Ludwigsburg 26.05.2024 Baden-Württemberg

Mycena meliigena 💗 #tinyfungi 

If you’ve watched my stories you might have seen me visit these and bring them back to life with a little rain water 🤣 the fruiting bodies are approximately 5mm TINY 

My third year observing these 😁 always a pleasure. #mycenameliigena

post_text:
Plant pot mushrooms keeping me entertained during the dry spell. 🥵 

Possibly something along the lines of Tulosesus / Coprinopsis 🤷‍♂️ I find these pretty challenging to ID even with microscopy and they have such short life cycles! appearing and disappearing in a day. 👉 the video shows a slightly more mature mushroom. Compost coprinoids ❤️🥰
IG_auto_desc: Photo by Max Mudie on August 05, 2022.

post_text:
Southern Bracket (Ganoderma australe) is another large bracket fungi similar to the Artist's Bracket (Ganoderma applanatum) but has thicker edges,  larger pores and darker tops. It grows to the same large size of 50cm as shown in pic 2.

post_text:
Have 3 ♥️

Much needed night with my bestie 🕺🏽🪩 

The last 2 weeks, and the next 2 weeks, are crazy busy with work, studying and extraaaaaaas 

I was so tempted this week to just stay in and be a hermit 

But it’s so important to take time ‘off’ and enjoy yourself 🙏🏼 

Another sober rave ticked off too ✅ 

For anyone considering it, do it, try it out 

Good vibes and company is what you need

And no come down or hangover the next day 🥰😂

#sobercurious #girlsnight #selfie #bristol #happy
IG_auto_desc: Photo shared by Nicole | Women’s Health and Wellbeing Coach on May 26, 2024 tagging @charlotte_cowgill_. May be a selfie of 2 people, blonde hair, people smiling and top.

post_text:
Here are various stages of growth of Mycena manipularis (syn.=Filoboletus/Favolaschia manipularis) aka “Luminous Porecaps”.

While these are bioluminescent - I show what they look like in daylight. 

Note: the second image has a different species in the mix, as Luminous Porecaps (as the name suggests-have pores, not gills). 

It’s interesting to see how some start out with a dark tan cap and then fade and lighten to a milky, translucent white as they age.
IG_auto_desc: Photo by Joseph Pallante on January 19, 2024.

post_text:
Growing your own shiitake mushrooms on logs in your garden is surprisingly easy. You inoculate some wood, wait a year or two (yes, it does require a bit of patience) and then, one rainy day, you get a harvest of homegrown shiitakes! And then more and more from those same logs each year, for about the next five years.⁠
⁠
Once you get into the swing of it, you can inoculate a few additional logs each autumn - ensuring a never-ending harvest and thus plenty of big warming bowls of mushroom ramen and stir-fried shiitake and everything delicious and wonderful.⁠
⁠
So, want to know exactly what we mean by 'inoculate logs'?⁠
⁠
At the link in our bio, we have a free Getting Started With Mushroom Cultivation guide, which includes a section on how to grow shiitake on logs. It'll help get your head around the basics, including:⁠

🪵 What supplies you need.⁠
🪵 How to prepare your substrate.⁠
🪵 Inoculation and incubation.⁠
🪵 And a little trick we learned to help bring on fruiting.⁠
⁠
Alrighty, lovely - go download your guide, have a read and then let us know if you have any questions? We're always here to help. Happy mushrooming! 🪵⁠
⁠
[Image description: Shiitake mushroom growing from logs.]⁠
⁠

post_text: We know fungi make a huge difference to the life of our garden, but we are only beginning to learn how they work. Today the NY Times has a fascinating article about a scientist who is working to map all the fungi in the world, though only a small proportion of them are even known. But you have to start somewhere. A link to the piece is in a Story we posted just now.

post_text:
King Alfred's Cakes (posh name: daldina concentrica) sporing

Inedible

Ascospores are ejected from the perithecia of these fruiting bodies as dust like spore - but in windless conditions they can and do stick together to form stringy cobweb like projections which grow in length as more spores are ejected and attach to the growing strands

So cool to see and photograph this! I found these specimens in a little sheltered clearing within woodland, relatively well protected from wind

✌️

post_text:
Harvest time has arrived for round 2 of the @mycopunks test all in one block colonised with Flammulina Velutipes

We also learned forking the mycelium does not appear to anything good; the mushrooms only really grew from the intact unforced side - and they grew well!

And WHAT IS UP WITH THE SLUGS THIS YEAR?! This one somehow managed to get into the greenhouse and climb 3 sets of shelves to get onto this block

Rehydrating this block overnight and then back to the greenhouse it goes

✌️

post_text:
Hoof Fungus (posh name: fomes fomentarius)

Inedible

Loads of hoof Fungus spotted today, in a predominantly Birch and Pine woodland. All over the Birch Trees - and this made a nice change seeing lots of this instead of Birch polypore, which tend to be much more common. Weirdly, barely any of that! 

✌️

post_text:
THE WAIT IS OVER!🍄🎉 After a three-year hiatus, we are thrilled to announce that the Santa Cruz Fungus Fair is returning to London Nelson this January.

We're proud to be co-presenting this 50th Anniversary celebration with @scfungusfed who helped us launch the inaugural event at the Museum in 1974. Together we're bringing back this unique Santa Cruz institution for what we hope is its best year yet!

Mark your calendars for January 12-14, 2024👇

Friday 1/12 2-5 PM
Saturday 1/13 10 AM - 5 PM
Sunday 1/14 10 AM - 5 PM

Link in bio to get advanced tickets and see program schedule. Tickets also available at the door (limited capacity for presentations).

post_text:
It's Thlimemold Thursday so enjoy this amazing specimen of Wasp's Nest Slime Mold A.K.A. Metatrichia vesparia which I found on dead Oak. This springtime slime gets it's common name from the shape of the Sporotheca (spore body holsters) which form in firmly united clusters much like the structure of a wasp's nest 🐝🔍👀

post_text:
Níscalo – Robellón – Callampa rosada
.
El género Lactarius comprende casi 600 especies ectomicorrícicas pertenecientes a la familia Russulaceae. Su mayor característica es la segregación de un látex de color que varía según la especie y que tiene apariencia lechosa, cualidad que le da el epíteto a su género, pues Lactarius proviene del latín “lac” que significa “leche”, siendo el ejemplar probablemente más conocido Lactarius deliciosus.
.
Esta especie se encuentra en plantaciones forestales de Pinus radiata en Chile y su aparición es otoñal e invernal, aunque en ciertas condiciones puede extender incluso hasta verano. Es una seta muy fácil de identificar, a grandes rasgos: tiene una forma de embudo, es quebradizo, con sombrero de color crema a anaranjado, convexo que se aplana con la edad, sobre la superficie del píleo tiene círculos concéntricos; las láminas son adnadas y decurrentes, de color naranjo vivo o zanahoria, al rasgarlas exuda el látex y este se oxida con la presencia de aire dejando un color verdoso; y el pie es cilíndrico, concolor al sombrero, macizo al inicio y luego hueco. 
.
Se trata de una especie muy distintiva por estas características, sin embargo hay otra especie muy parecida en el país: L. quieticolor, que correspondería a la imagen, pues tiene un sombrero mucho más pálido y blanquecino a diferencia de L. deliciosus que tiene el sombrero más anaranjado fuerte y que en apreciación del profesor Gotz es la especie que estaría mayormente en Chile en las plantaciones de pino insigne. 
.
.
Lactarius quieticolor Romagn.
.
.

post_text:
Meet mold—a fascinating form of fungi! Mold plays a crucial role in nature by breaking down and recycling organic material. 🌱

While it’s not something you want on your food or in your home, mold is everywhere, thriving in moist environments and helping decompose everything from fallen leaves to leftovers in your fridge. One of nature’s best recyclers! 🔄♻️

Curious to learn more about how mold works and its role in the ecosystem? Check out the Mold lesson in our ‘Activities for Kids’ in our online resources! Link in bio. 👆

@fungifoundation @fundacionfungi 

#Mold #Funglossary #FungiFoundation #FungiEducation #Funga #FungiKingdom #ActivitiesForKids
IG_auto_desc: Photo by Fungi Education on June 05, 2024. May be an image of text that says 'MOLD Mold is α fungus that grows in multicellular filaments called hyphae, thriving in moist spaces and reproducing by releasing tiny, airborne spores. Mold breaks down and recycles organic materials. Thousands of fungi grow as S mold and can appear in many colors, such as black, gray, green, blue, orange, or pink. Funglossary by Fungi Education'.

𝙍𝙚𝙞𝙣𝙤 𝙁𝙪𝙣𝙜𝙞 𝙉°8
El micelio emerge desde el bajo suelo, en forma de hongo, siembra sus esporas y trasciende en el tiempo. Lo habitual es haberlas visto formando  grupos de varios individuos. Algunas, en soledad contribuyen a dar belleza única al escenario, no se porqué las imagino en silencio. 
Lo siento parte de la magia del reino.
La fotografía  me ha permitido saber de esa magia.

𝙍𝙚𝙞𝙣𝙤 𝙁𝙪𝙣𝙜𝙞 𝙉°9
He aprendido que este reino es muy amplio. Extendido bajo tierra, los micelios entrelazados con las raices del bosque recorren kilómetros. Estos pequeños hongos de no más de 2 a 3 cm emergen para entregar sus esporas. Tendido en el suelo para llevarnos sus imágenes, apreciamos su sutil y fragil belleza y  construyendo  historias aportamos a la magia del reino.

Miniscule blue-green elven cup🧝🧚‍♀️ (Chlorociboria aeruginascens)⠀
⠀
⠀
Wood infected with Chlorociboria fungi has long been used in such decorative woodworking as Tunbridgeware. In Italy the practice dates at least to the 14th century🙌⠀
⠀
⠀
This mainly winter-fruiting funguses fruit is rare to encounter but you can find evidence of the Fungus by looking for green rot on decaying oak trees☄️🌌🌳

post_text:
Feast on yeast, the tiny powerhouse responsible for some of your favorite foods and drinks! 🍺☕️

Yeast is a single-celled fungus that can reproduce itself asexually through budding and plays a vital role in the culinary world, especially in baking and brewing. 🍞

These types of fungi work by converting sugars into carbon dioxide and alcohol in a process called fermentation.
 
🔬 But yeast isn't just for food and drink—it's also crucial in biotechnology for developing medications and environmental efforts to produce biofuels. 💊

💣 There is even a species of yeast that has been studied for its potential ability to work as a bioremediator in TNT-polluted marine environments. 

🧐 As you can see, humans have had an intimate relationship with this fungus for thousands of years. 

📚 Head to the Yeast lesson in the ‘Activities for Kids’ section of our online curriculum for some fun yeast education exercises! Link in bio.

Pero gracias a una publicación de @giulifungi descubrimos que era una Plectania chilensis, más conocida como Milcao de Monte. Buen lunes ☀️

post_text:
No son plantas, tampoco animales, entonces... ¿Qué son? 🤔🍄

Las setas o callampas que solemos ver en otoño, de diversas formas, tamaños y colores son la parte exterior de algunos hongos que viven bajo tierra o dentro de la materia orgánica en descomposición 🦠🍄

Los hongos son uno de los cinco reinos en que se agrupan a los seres vivos y, por lo tanto, no se consideran ni plantas, ni animales 🍄

No son vegetales, pues no realizan fotosíntesis. Tampoco son animales, pues no ingieren su alimento, lo absorben y sus células tienen pared celular 🧬🍄

Debido a estas razones estos organismos están situados en su propio reino biológico llamado Fungi 🍄

Está es solo una de las muchas curiosidades que podemos aprender sobre estos importantes y lindos seres vivos 🥹🍄

Aprovecho que es otoño temporada donde los vemos por todas partes, así iré enseñando fotitos y videos de las variedades que encontré por estos lados, y por supuesto otras curiosidades sobre ellos 🍄🍄

Recuerda darle amor a este post 💚

#hongo #otoño #hongos #fungi #vidafungi #fungilove #naturaleza #plantas #lamacetitachile #fungichile #valdivia #amanita #amanitas

post_text:
.
Llueve en el bosque esclerófilo.
Escucho la lluvia. La disfruto.
Pienso en la tierra nutriéndose, refrescándose.
Pienso en esa humedad que penetra en los micelios y que los hará  fructificar pronto. 
La vida continua.

Sarcoscypha coccinea, crece en ramas muertas. Fructifica en invierno principios de primavera. 
Esta belleza tan llamativa, la fotografié en agosto en Altos de Cantillana. 
.
.
.

"𝑳𝑨𝑴𝑬𝑳𝑨𝑺"
.
👉 Las lamelas o laminas, son delicadas estructuras bajo el sombrero, no solo son bellas sino esenciales. Transportan las esporas 👀, el verdadero poder de la reproducción fúngica 🍄

¿Sabías que su disposición puede ayudarnos a identificar especies? 

¿Sabes que hongo es el de las fotografías?
. 
. 
👉 Si te ha gustado este contenido, dale like, comenta y comparte, así Instagram me ayuda a llegar a más personas como tu 😊.
.
.

post_text:
Agradecida de la invitación de la salida que realizó @fungo.trip el domingo pasado a reconocer hongos del cerro ñielol 

Acá algunos registros

Variadas y coloridas Mycenas

1. Mycena cyanocephala 
2. Mycena haematopus
3. Mycena chusqueophila

La famosa Melena de León 

4. Hericium cf. coraloides

El último no me lo esperaba y me sorprendió mucho al verlo

5. Hygroporus nothofagi

Me gustan estas excursiones, son muy amigables y de mucho aprendizaje.
Que se repitan ❤️

#fungichile
#fungachilena 
#cerroñielol 
#temuco
#mycena #hericium #hygroporus
IG_auto_desc: Photo shared by Marta George Fotografia on May 23, 2024 tagging @fungo.trip. May be an image of mushroom and text.

El "Funga Festival Temuco y Padre las Casas" se celebrará los días 15 y 16 de junio en el Centro Cultural Padre las Casas (Maquehue #1441).

Este festival único busca generar un impacto social significativo, contribuyendo al desarrollo económico, turístico y cultural de nuestra comunidad.

Descubre el fascinante mundo de los hongos a través de excursiones, charlas, música, arte y una feria con productos relacionados, desde diseño y textil hasta gastronomía gourmet. post_text:
Amanita muscaria, Fly Agaric, Amanitaceae. An introduced species to Australia, it is mycorrhizal with northern hemisphere conifers and hardwoods.

 Autumn and winter is when A. muscaria dominates the pine forests of Australia, though after the amount of rainfall we have had this summer, it’s not unusual to have them popping up now, in the same way Lactarius deliciosus (saffron milk cap) has been plentiful this summer. I was puzzled when I found this, as it was in the middle of a Eucalyptus forest, though after looking around I found two Pinus radiata growing a little way away. 

 Known around the world for a variety of reasons, it has been portrayed in folklore, prepared in the kitchen for food, as medicine, and as a hallucinogen (it contains ibotenic acid, a neurotoxin which converts to muscimol, a psychoactive compound, once digested). 

 Amanita muscaria poses a serious threat to the biodiversity of native fungi in the Myrtle Beech forests of Victoria and Tasmania, where it has formed Mycohrriza with Nothofagus cunninghamii.

post_text:
Сегодня была разведка по белым. Попадались редко, небольшими группами, в основном на окраинах леса. Были как молодые экземпляры, так и уже переростки. Червивость около 60 процентов.

post_text:
Remember the little Prince I was keeping an eye on? Well, I thought I may have left him waiting too long and that he wouldn't be there for me when I returned... but he was! 🤴Cape and all.
. 
He grew up to be big and handsome, and even has a little brother. The first time I harvested a large one of these the gills were still a creamy colour with a hint of pink. Now look at these! Absolutely beautiful! The younger brother had some lighter gills which deserve a post of their own.
.
I'll be having these for lunch!
.
🔬Agaricus augustus 🇬🇧 The Prince
IG_auto_desc: Photo by Laura on October 10, 2018.

post_text:
It’s always a delight to find a pop of color in the woods during the winter months. 🧡

The fruiting bodies of the mock oyster are a lovely sherbet orange with fuzzy caps and crowded gills. They drop a very pale pink spore print, so be sure when conducting a print to use white paper.
Most people say they stink, but I’ve never experienced that when finding these. 
They can be found growing in clustered rows on dead hardwood trees, but can also be found on conifers. 

🆔: Phyllotopsis nidulans | mock oyster
.
.
.

post_text:
Gallacea Scleroderma is one of New Zealand’s varieties of pouch fungi with fleshy, enclosed fruiting bodies. Truffles are ascomycete fungi, but most of these New Zealand pouch fungi are basidiomycetes. The gills are packed tight inside the pouch and they sit in many different genera. . Their spores are thought to be often spread by birds. They are very cool fungi.

post_text:
It's Thlimemold Thursday so enjoy this amazing specimen of Wasp's Nest Slime Mold A.K.A. Metatrichia vesparia which I found on dead Oak. This springtime slime gets it's common name from the shape of the Sporotheca (spore body holsters) which form in firmly united clusters much like the structure of a wasp's nest 🐝🔍👀

post_text:
Can you spot the sandfly? 
Gliophorus sp. that doesn’t quite fit visually with any of the usual players in this species in New Zealand. We became enamoured with its pretty, albeit slimy, cap and stipe. 

The south Island of New Zealand is famous or should I say infamous for its scourge of vicious sandflies? Ouch.

post_text:
Hexagonia tenuis fungi is plentiful in the regenerating native forests at the base of the escarpment. These areas were originally cleared for farmland and mining. The returning forests are only approximately 50 years into the process of establishing themselves again and I'm always in awe of their regenerative power. 

It's hard not to amorphosize natural phenomena with the constraints our language puts upon us. Fungi networks are described like the internet, beehives are described like officeworkers, but we know this is a crude way to narrate the complexity, abstraction, mystery and full expression of nature. So I tread tentatively knowing these words that follow are inept, but to experience a regenerating forest is to be part of a continual homecoming. 

With each species of native flora and fauna that returns I personally am exalted but there is no fanfare, fireworks or roll call within the forest itself. Instead a palatable gathering of strength and an emerging tranquillity spreads as each species reestablishes itself within the dynamics of the forest family. 

Many of the photos in this gallery are from this regenerating forest and it is a joy to share the homecoming of species like this fungi with you.

The returning forests are only approximately 50 years into the process of establishing themselves again and I'm always in awe of their regenerative power. 

It's hard not to amorphosize natural phenomena with the constraints our language puts upon us. Fungi networks are described like the internet, beehives are described like officeworkers, but we know this is a crude way to narrate the complexity, abstraction, mystery and full expression of nature. So I tread tentatively knowing these words that follow are inept, but to experience a regenerating forest is to be part of a continual homecoming. 

With each species of native flora and fauna that returns I personally am exalted but there is no fanfare, fireworks or roll call within the forest itself. Instead a palatable gathering of strength and an emerging tranquillity spreads as each species reestablishes itself within the dynamics of the forest family. 

Many of the photos in this gallery are from this regenerating forest and it is a joy to share the homecoming of species like this fungi with you.

post_text: A repost of one of my favourite photos of 2021 for the #sony12daysoflenses12 competition. A ‘waterfall’ of eggs spilling from the Nidula niveotomentosa or birds nest fungi cups. Water droplets drop into the cups dispersing the ‘eggs’ which release the spores. So tiny but so very cool to see. Focus stacked images from Sony A7riii and my favourite 90mm macro lens. #fungiphotography #mycelium #fungi  #fantasticfungi #mushrooms #fungifanatic  #mycology #naturephotography #mushroomphotography #fungihunting #mushroomguerrilla #mushrooms.ig #forest_floor #naturephotography  #macro #nuts_about_macro  #macro_captures  #macro_nature #macrophtography  #macro_perfection #raw_nature #raw_allnature #raw_macro #sonyalpha.anz #sonya7riii #sony90mmmacro #sony12daysoflenses12 @sonyalpha.anz

post_text:
Brown bells of death ☠️⚰️😱

Galerina patagonica has a Gondwanan distribution and grows from rotting wood 

It contains the same deadly amatoxins that are found in the infamous death caps (Amanita phalloides). Same goes for other species nested within the Galerina marginata complex

Galerina patagonica doesn't have its own common name but common names of the more widely distributed Galerina marginata include the funeral bell, deadly skullcap, autumn skullcap or deadly Galerina

post_text:
Cerrena zonata looks like turkey tail fungi from the top but underneath you feel like you have been plunged into a cave full of stalactites and drapery formations. I love how the fruiting bodies of fungi can change a space. Just visually these shapeshifters can transport you under the ocean, underground or distant solar systems and make you forget you're standing in the forest.

post_text:
Me hace tan feliz saber que se vienen los Festivales de Hongos 👉🍄👈

Espacios maravillosos de aprendizaje, de compartir, de conocer, de caminar, bailar, actualizarse y ver a los fungiamig-s 💜

Mayo es el mes en que la Funga se reúne a hablar de Hongos, a darle la voz al Bosque 🌳 y lo importante que es resguardar los lugares en dónde habitan los Honguitos! 

🌟Comenzaremos con el hermoso 👉 @festivalreinofungi que se ha destacado en la Región de La Araucania especialmente por el Carnaval que convoca a gran parte de la comunidad, y llena la ciudad de colores, música y magia 
🍄3, 4 & 5 de Mayo
📍Pucón

🌟Luego uno de los Festivales más antiguos en Chile el maravilloso 👉@fungifest en la Capital de los Hongos de Chile, Valdivia! 
Destaca por ser un encuentro multitudinario que auna desde las artes, las ciencias, la fungicocina, los recolectores tradicionales, la música, y un abanico de interdisciplinas que se convocan a maravillarnos y enamorarnos de la Funga 🍄
🍄17, 18 y 19 de Mayo
📍Valdivia

🌟 Para comenzar con la fungicidad del Bosque Esclerófilo en el sorprendente @festivalfungiconcepcion 👁️ que el año pasado nos sorprendió porque duró más de 10 días 🙏🏻 y fue fungifantabuloso! 
Ademas, los amigos de @concefunga nos han enseñado cómo el trabajo colectivo y en simbiosis puede realizar grandes cambios, aprendizajes y alianzas a nivel glocal! 
🍄24, 25 y 26
📍 Concepción

Gracias a todas las personas que hacen posibles los Festivales de Hongos en Chile, sabemos que es una gran labor de organización, de logística y que muchas veces es completamente autogestionado y cada uno de sus organizadores ha dado lo mejor de si para acercarnos a la naturaleza, la Madre Tierra que nos necesita! 

Gracias a cada uno!

Newentuleymiiii evoca a la fuerza que hay en ti!
Newentuleymun en nosotr-s! 

PD: faltan fechas, pero por mientras las principales para que las apunten en su agenda! 
.
.
#hongos 
#fungifest 
#festivalreinofungi 
#conce

post_text: FungiFest 2020: el festival de hongos más importante de Latinoamérica llegará a nuestros hogares 🍄🌿‼️ ¡Les tenemos una increíble invitación a partir del próximo lunes 15 de junio! A todos los fanáticos de los hongos, y a los que quieren conocer más de ellos, es tiempo de ponerse en #ModoMicelio y disfrutar desde nuestros hogares las entretenidas actividades de la quinta versión de @FungiFest. Todos los años, este festival se celebra en Valdivia, pero esta versión se podrá disfrutar de manera online. La programación del festival incluye charlas, talleres, concursos y conversatorios sobre gastronomía fúngica, recolección, cultivo de hongos, ciencia y cultura. Todo esto bajo la compañía del “Profesor Entoloma”, el personaje inspirado en el hongo oficial del FungiFest 2020, el Entoloma necopinatum. En laderasur.com te entregamos más detalles. @fungi_foundation @mutantesproducciones #laderasur #fungifest #elfuturoesfungi #thinkfungi
IG_auto_desc: Photo by Ladera Sur 🌎 on June 12, 2020.

post_text:
Hoy tuvimos un entretenido taller de introducción al grabado, en el marco del calendario de otoño de @fungifest 🍄 
Revisamos elementos introductorios del grabado, distintos tamaños y materiales para matrices, pasando por la ilustración y grabado, para terminar con la impresión manual con cuchara de palo 🔥 
Cómo el tema era relacionado al reino fungi, cada asistente se lanzó en la elaboración de su gráfica para explorar el estampado en papel. 
Gracias a extensión de la UACh que me facilito en convenio el espacio (donde se vienen otras actividades más este año) y a FungiFest que integró esta mediación en el calendario de sus actividades, estoy muy agradecido tras esta semana modo fungi 🍄 
———— 
Y con esta actividad, finaliza mi periodo de otoño con lo que tenía planificado de marzo a la fecha. Partió con el desarrollo de las gráficas, un viaje a Santiago, luego Pucón, para terminar en Valdivia compartiendo en itinerancia la serie “Esporada Gráfica”, que el fin de semana pasado monté en el festival como parte de un proceso creativo de grabado. De que estuvo weno, lo estuvo 🍄👀 Bacán la gente que conocí y con quienes compartimos espacios gráficos, espero nos veamos pronto por acá o por allá. Porque el grabado se defiende desde el grabado, a preparar lo de septiembre y de cabeza en los soportes, ya les cuento de eso 🙂 

#grabado #fungifest #tallerdegrabado #linografia #linocut #mushrooms🍄

@hostdefense is a brand that specializes in creating mushroom-based supplements. Their products are formulated using organic mushrooms grown on their own farm, Fungi Perfecti, located in Washington State, USA. Host Defense is known for its commitment to quality, sustainability, and ethical practices in mushroom cultivation and supplement production. They offer a wide range of mushroom-based supplements, including capsules, extracts, and powders, each designed to support various aspects of health and wellness. The brand's founder, Paul Stamets, is a renowned mycologist and advocate for the use of mushrooms for health and environmental purposes.

This article dives into the components of what's inside Host Defense products! 
Click the link to check out why it's important to read and understand important certification/designation symbols, and why you should be selecting brands that are committed to the highest standards. 

We hope you enjoy this article as much as we do! You can also click the link in our bio!

post_text: Paul Stamets presents Amadou hats before a lecture “Mushrooms, Mycelium and the Mycology of Consciousness” to Lillooet First@Nation T'ít'q'et Community, St'át'imc Nation, Lillooet, BC, Canada. Tribal Chief of T'ít'q'et Shelley Leech assisted by Candice “Falling Water”’Jack welcomed me to their community to share knowledge about mushrooms and mycelium. The interest in mushrooms is a mycelial bridge across cultures and time. I am honored to be one messenger of many. Mushrooms connect us all to each other and to the Earth. #mycology #fungi #fungiperfecti #amadou #mushrooms #ethnomycology

MycoBrew® Cocoa WHIPPED CREAM!

Treat yourself to 800mg of Lion’s Mane mushroom mycelium with Host Defense® MycoBrew Cocoa Whipped Cream.

Try out this convenient recipe by adding the ingredients straight into your mug:

INGREDIENTS:

- About ½ cup of heavy cream (depending on your mug size)
- 1 tbsp (or packet) of Host Defense MycoBrew Cocoa
- About 1 tsp of powdered sugar (depending on your mug size)
- Freshly brewed coffee

INSTRUCTIONS:

- Add heavy cream, MycoBrew Cocoa, and powdered sugar directly into your mug. No extra dishes required!
- MIX IT UP with your Host Defense Frother until thick and smooth.
- Pour in the coffe.
- Enjoy!

post_text:
I’m a true believer in antibiotics in my media. I never make up agar without the addition of gentamicin. To put it plainly antibiotics will  help keep your cultures younger longer and resistant to bacterial infection. Just like with humans that have had staph infections and are more prone to have staff infections after having one mushroom cultures operate the same way. From my experience if a culture has been sick or infected it will be susceptible to sickness from that point on. If you don’t want to source the antibiotics yourself to add them to your mix you can buy premade antibiotic agar from Paul Stamets’ company @fungiperfecti. I highly recommend getting antibiotics worked  into your lab programs if you have a good culture and want it to last for years without issues. 
#gentamicin #antibiotic #agar #fungiperfecti #mycotek 
#monoculture #labwork #mycology #culturemedia

post_text: It’s always nice that fall gives us one more boom of mushrooms out east before winter sets in and life halts for a few months. It seems like the fall mushroom season here is mostly saprophytic species like this Mycena as well as Laetiporus, Grifola, Pleurotus, and others. Summer is the peak for the good edible mycorrhizal species like black trumpets, chanterelles, boletes, Lactarius and Russulas. #mycology #mycena #bonnets #mushroom #shroomatnoon #mushrooms #fungi #fungiperfecti #gills #mushroomgills #basidiomycota #natureupclose #decomposer

post_text:
Growing a new fungus is always interesting. This is Cordyceps militaris #cordycepsmilitaris a fungi that until recently was not allowed to be grown here in Australia. Now we can legally grow this, I was curious to give it a go - especially after investing so much time into trying to grow Cordyceps gunnii, unsuccessfully!

Not my best grow! And I have been watching lots of US growers really get to dial these in to be an art. But I grew these on white rice with no nutrients to start out so I could get an idea of growth, yield, and other characteristics that may help later! One big hint, don't try to grow these when it is hot without cooling!

We are all about creative cultivation! 🌀 ⠀
⠀
Here in Guatemala we do not have easy access to a lot of equipment, like jars. So when all of our jars are occupied we come up with something new! ☄️⠀
⠀
This tek has some up and downsides....⠀
Upside☝️: It is really easy to evenly spread your grain spawn to your bulk substrate⠀
Downside👇: If the mycelium is too strong to break while shaking, well.... You have some nice decoration for your room 😂

post_text:
These miniature white mushrooms are part of a large genus of small saprotrophic mushrooms called Mycena that are rarely more than a few centimeters in width. They are characterized by a white spore print, a small conical or bell-shaped cap, and a thin fragile stem. Most are gray or brown, but a few species have brighter colors.⠀
.⠀
Repost from @mycophoria 📸 by: @corikindred ⠀
Check them both out for more fungal awesomeness.

post_text:
A Fungi Nomade Fest 🍄‍🟫 

Last week’s weather was all over the place. From blazing sun and pouring rain, to even hail on the same day! 

Even with harsh weather changes like these, there is one #supercrop that can grow year-round in a controlled indoor environment, and still be incredibly #sustainable 🌱 @ilfungoeclettico 👀‼️

Considering the drastic changes of temperature in one day, we wanted to satisfy both warm and cold cravings ✨

For the zuppa di giorno, @pinasiotto went with a twist on the iconic #Pancotto but with fungi, chives, asparagi, and a generous sprinkle of Parmigiano 💛

I took the lead with a Fungiche, a #plantbased twist on a #PeruvianCeviche 🇵🇪 Slow-cooked #Pleurotus Florida marinated in tomato water, red onion, lemon and orange juice 🍊 For a sweet and smoky taste, we added charred bell peppers, and finished with a celery, ginger, and cilantro “leche de tigre” 🐯

🧆 As a bonus, of course I got to try their Lentil Falafel with a cucumber pico de gallo and smoked eggplant sauce 

Once again, I am so thankful for this empowering hub that continues to encourage me to let go of fears and just have fun(gi) 🤣💜 @cristina_fiorese

IG_auto_desc: Photo shared by Sophie the girl who eaaaats on May 26, 2024 tagging @pastonomade, and @ilfungoeclettico. May be an image of shiitake mushrooms, congee, asparagus and grits.

post_text:
This structure caught my attention as it harmonizes with nature, so I stopped to take a picture of it. I originally thought this was a coffee shop in the middle of a mountain road, away from houses but right in front of a temple. It’s just naturally beautiful in every angle. 

Later, I found out that it was a wood-ear beverage and sausage shop. The owners were so hospitable and kind to show us their fruiting room. They cultivate the mushroom by themselves and process it into a beverage. 

I like wood-ear beverages because they are healthy. Also, it contains substances which are good for our overall health. So I bought three bottles. Besides the beverage, I bought the pink mushroom, which tasted so good when cooked with ginger and seasoned with soy sauce. 

#miaoli #miaolitravel #miaolifood #woodearmushrooms #woodear #fungicultura #fungiculture #taiwantravels #taiwanmountain #mountainview #natureshots
IG_auto_desc: Photo by am_remina on May 28, 2024. May be an image of road and street.
