Funny Mushroom Shirt-”In a World of Flowers, Be a Mushroom” printed on a Gildan 64000 with DTG method. Starting at $15.17

Want a cool and unique way to show that you love mushrooms? This funny mushroom shirt is all you need! This shirt will look great with your other clothes, whether you like to garden or just hang out in the woods. Also, it makes a great gift for mushroom fans!

This lovely modern aesthetic t-shirt is a wonderful present for people who love the outdoors, mushrooms, or just being outside in general. This shirt is also cool and comfy for you, and it looks great too. Get yours right away!!

*DETAILS

The soft-style, short sleeved t-shirt for both men and women is a new take on casual comfort. The shoulders have twill tape on them to make them last longer. It doesn't have any side seams. Ribbed knitting was used to make the collar so that it won't curl up.

The design is a cute mushroom print with “In a world of flowers be a mushroom” written on it. Graphic is professionally printed using leading industry equipment with a “direct to garment” (DTG) method. This is not vinyl. See the production notes below.

This t-shirt is made of very soft, solid colored cotton. Polyester is used for Heather colors and sports gray. The "natural" color is made with unprocessed cotton, which results in small black flecks throughout the fabric. 

Please review the size chart to ensure you receive the fit you want.

Size and color options are available using the drop down menu. 

Colors can vary. Please understand the actual color may vary slightly from your monitor. We cannot guarantee that the color you see accurately illustrates the true color of the product.

Care instructions: See listing for details.

I love jelly ears! Last year I decided to actively try some fungiculture and create a jelly ear habitat within the hedge so I could up my haul. I harvested some elder of my trees and lay it horizontally so that it would rot quicker and hopefully become inoculated. And this year viola!

post_text:
"Magic Mushroom Cultivation” by Steven Pollock M.D. (1977) is one of the legendary texts in the cultivation of "magic mushrooms". Many popular books were published in the US during the 70’s about the cultivation of Psilocybe spp., but this one stands out as one of the better known, particularly because in time Pollock was (incorrectly) associated with the cubensis strain "P envy". Pollock is also well known for finding and cultivating P. tampanensis, aka "Philosophers Stones".

Psilocybe cubensis is one of the most cultivated mushrooms, and as a consequence of extensive collection, cultivation, breeding, and marketing ploys by various spore print sellers numerous “strains” now exist. Unfortunately, much of the history of many of the older strains has been lost, or exist within obfuscated narratives from a variety of websites, with the person/s responsible having disappeared into history.

Cailleux and Heim were the first to grow cultures of P. cubensis (as Stropharia cubensis), publishing their methods in 1957. During the late 1960’s and early 1970’s, those with access to scientific literature adapted laboratory techniques for the cultivation of Psilocybe spp., notably R.E. Brown and associates who published “The Psychedelic Guide to the Preparation of the Eucharist in a Few of Its Many Guises” which was the first countercultural text to mention the cultivation of P. cubensis.

Other books include “Growing Wild Mushrooms” by Harris (1976), “Psilocybin: Magic Mushroom Grower's Guide” by Oss & Oeric (1976), “How to Identify and Grow Psilocybin Mushrooms” by Gutierrez & Stevens (1977), “Teonanácatl : hallucinogenic mushrooms of North America” by Ott & Bigwood (1978), and “The mushroom Cultivator” by Stamets and Chilton(1983)

post_text:
💙 Happy World Water Day! 🌊 

Without water, there is no us and no mushrooms. 

Our town Tzununa, is named after the indiginous name of the lake. Tzunu = hummingbird, na=water. 

Water is also a challenge here, all of our waters are invested with parasites like E.Coli, Giardia and many more unwanted visitors. We are blessed enough to be able to properly filter our water, not all of our local neighbors have this ability.

It is in this spirit that we, feel so passionate about water quality in our home of Lake Atitlan, Guatemala. We have since partnered with a local NGO, ​@water4lifeglobal
​
Water 4 Life Global is working to provide families in Guatemala access to clean water. Their clean water initiatives include the distribution of water filter technology, collaboration on biological water treatment plans and contributions towards the reforestation of Lake Atitlán.
​
The greater vision of Water 4 Life Global is nothing less than the availability of clean drinking water that is easily accessible and sustained for many years. Their team envisions a life free of water transmitted diseases, water toxins, malnutrition, and environmental damage, in a country that maintains each of these issues as very viable threats to the communities and ecosystems.

As a monthly donor, we proudly stand by the work of Water 4 Life Global. 
When you enroll in our Sacred Mushroom Cultivation Course, you too are supporting indigenous families and the waterways of Tzununa, Guatemala.

Tap the link in our @fungiacademy bio to learn about growing your own mushrooms while supporting this cause 💧🍄

post_text:
Of more than a hundred compounds measured in the bloodstreams of thousands of individuals, the one most associated with the lowest rates of disease and death was an amino acid called ergothioneine. Higher blood levels were associated with lower risk of heart disease, stroke, and death from all causes put together over a period of more than 20 years.

Ergothioneine was discovered more than a century ago, but it was ignored until recently, when researchers found that humans have a highly specific transporter protein in our bodies specifically designed to pull ergothioneine out of food and into body tissue.

What are the best dietary sources of ergothioneine? It isn’t made by plants or animals––only fungi, like mushrooms and certain soil bacteria. Plants can suck some up from the soil and animals who eat the plants can similarly benefit, but the highest levels by far have been reported in mushrooms. Mushrooms and tempeh—a fungi-fermented soybean cake—are the only concentrated dietary sources. As mushrooms go, shiitake and oyster mushrooms have higher levels than white button mushrooms. However, just eating a cup a day of ordinary white mushrooms can double ergothioneine concentrations in the blood.

Mushroom consumption is associated with a lower risk of cancer, driven mainly by lower breast cancer rates, as well as a lower risk of dying prematurely from all causes put together. Interventional trials have found, for example, that eating just a few mushrooms a day can improve immune function.

 How Not to Age is out now! Borrow a copy from your local library or order one today: https://see.nf/HNTABook

Watch the video “Dietary Sources of the ‘Longevity Vitamin’ Ergothioneine” at https://see.nf/ergo to learn more.

post_text:
🆔Inosperma erubescens (Inocybe erubescens)
👉🏽Deadly Fibrecap, brick-red tear mushroom 
👉🏽Ziegelroter Risspilz
👉🏽变红丝盖伞 (reddening silk top umbrella)

🌟 The brick-red splitting mushroom (Inocybe erubescens) can be found on forest paths, in parks, or in deciduous forests, especially under beech or linden trees on calcareous, nutrient-rich soils. 🌳🍃 The fruit bodies of this mushroom appear from spring/early summer until late autumn. 🌸🍂

🌟 磚紅裂褶菇（Inocybe erubescens）可以在林間小徑、公園或闊葉林中找到，特別是在含鈣、富營養的土壤中的山毛櫸或菩提樹下。🌳🍃 這種蘑菇的子實體從春季/初夏到晚秋出現。🌸🍂

⚠️ **WARNING:** Inocybe erubescens contains a potentially fatal dose of the toxin muscarine. ⚠️😱 However, its deadly toxicity depends on the amount consumed; a small piece might not cause severe illness, but eating an entire mushroom can be fatal. 🍄☠️

⚠️ **警告：** 磚紅裂褶菇含有致命劑量的毒素——毒蕈鹼。⚠️😱 然而，其致命毒性取決於攝入量；少量可能不會引起嚴重疾病，但食用整個蘑菇可能致命。🍄☠️

📚 All mushroom guidebooks and mushroom hunters advise against consuming any members of the Inocybaceae family! ❌🚫

📚 所有的蘑菇指南書和蘑菇獵人都建議不要食用任何Inocybaceae科的成員！❌🚫

Today, when I discovered these Inocybe mushrooms in the village next to some linden trees, I had to lie down on the ground to take pictures and examine them carefully. 📸👀 This was when a car stopped right behind me, and a man got out to ask if everything was okay. 🚗💨 I felt a bit awkward but reassured him that I was fine. 😅 It was heartening to see that people care if someone is spread out on the ground, regardless of the reason. ❤️🙏

今天，當我在村子裡的一些菩提樹旁發現這些裂褶菇時，我不得不躺在地上拍照並仔細檢查它們。📸👀 就在這時，一輛車停在我身後，一位男士下車問我是否一切正常。🚗💨 我感到有點尷尬，但我向他保證我沒事。😅 看到人們關心無論何種原因躺在地上的人，這讓我感到很暖心。❤️🙏

#InocybeErubescens 🍄🌿🕵️‍♂️

I tried some microscopy on this one. 🔬🧬 Image one shows cheilocystidia, and in between the two big cheilocystidia is a basidium with two sterigmata (they look like tiny antennas). 🧫🔍 The second microscopy image shows spores, which are oval to almond-shaped. I used Melzer's reagent to stain the sample. 🧪📸 
Oh my, microscopy terminology is really hard! Definitely need to catch up. 😅 In case you know any of the terms in Chinese, please feel free to comment. 
Cheilozystidia 緣擔孢子囊 
Basidia 擔子 
Sterigmata 擔梗

post_text:
Did you know that improper storage of grains and nuts could result in the production of a potent toxin? Aflatoxin B2 is mainly produced by the fungi Aspergillus flavus. Aflatoxin-producing molds are commonly detected in inadequately stored agricultural produce, including maize, rice, cassava, cottonseed, millet, sorghum, sesame seeds, sweetcorn, chili peppers, tree nuts, sunflower seeds, spices, and wheat. Aflatoxin B2, while not as toxic as Aflatoxin B1, can affect children, leading to delays in development and stunted growth. Prolonged exposure has also been linked to liver cancer and liver impairment.

post_text:
Have you seen any fungi in our local parks and reserves? It’s been a slow start for us here in northern Victoria with a very dry autumn and we’re jealous of all the fabulous fungi finds elsewhere! However, the odd fungus has been popping up…. and it looks like we’ll manage to sneak in some rain right as autumn turns to winter and then the hunt will really be on! 

This specimen of ‘white punk’ (Laetiporus portentosus) was found growing on a stringybark on the Granite Walking Trail (McFarlanes Hill) yesterday. You can see the pores on the underside. 

Fascinating fungi fact: This particular species has been used traditionally by both Aboriginal people and New Zealand Māori people as a tinder and for carrying fire as it will smoulder slowly when dry. 

#parklandsalburywodonga #mcfarlaneshill #alburywodonga #wodonga #walkingtrail #granitewalkingtrail #fungi #fungus #mushroom #whitepunk #fungifacts #mushroomsofinstagram #fungiphotography #fungilove #nature #autumn #mycology
IG_auto_desc: Photo by @parklandsalburywodonga on May 29, 2024. May be an image of puffball mushroom and mushroom.

We'd like to take the time to introduce you to the happy Coral Fungus (Ramaria sp). 🍄

You'd think this one would live under the sea with a name like coral, but it's actually ectomycorrihizal. 

This means it forms symbiotic relationships with roots of nearby trees. 🌳

Fascinating and very pretty! 😍😍

post_text:
Happy full moon #mushroomlovers 

🌑🌘🌗🌖🌕🌔🌓🌒🌑

#Repost from @symbiiotica 🍄

How do lunar cycles influence the cycles of fungi? 

Considering the fact that lunar gravity influences every being on this planet, especially water bodies and those with water-based bodies (most of life), and considering the fact that most mushrooms are > 90% water… it’s almost certain that the moons influences plays SOME role in fungal fruitings, behaviors and expressions. 

Many Indigenous cultures that have deeply rooted ethnomycological history, especially those of the northern hemisphere in Scandinavia and Siberia, claim that fruitings of ground-dwelling, fleshy macrofungi occur in greater abundance on the full moon.

Since the moons gravity pulls the terrestrial tides (ground water) further up to the surface of the soil on full moons and even more so on new moons, it would make sense that lunar events have a direct effect on fruiting of certain species. 

But for now the exact knowing of these influences stays happily shrouded in mystery.
What the moons exact role is in fungal cycles, we just don’t really know. 
And maybe we’ll never know.
And that’s okay. 
~ 

Here is a rendition of the basic life cycle of a basidiomycete mushroom cycling with the lunar phases.
From my perspective, I’ve matched the different energetic expressions of the mushroom life cycle with the associated energetic expressions of the lunar cycle. 
From full; the biggest, boldest, brightest expression of the mature, sporulating fruiting body, to new; the deep, dark inquisitive phase of underground, rhizospheric mycelial navigation, and back again. 

In the center is the Elder Futhark Norse Rune, Inguz. The Elder Futhark runic alphabet is said to be the most ancient form of the many Indigenous writing systems from my Scandinavian ancestral lineages(s). Inguz or “the God, Ing” is the rune of fertility and new beginnings, marking a new phase of life. Also interpreted as a seed, the birthing of a new idea or life form. The shape also represents a doorway, the portal to the astral planes.

I’ve been partnering with @fungiacademy since the beginning - for both of us! They are a global leader in mushroom education, and I’m honored to collaborate with them in creating fulfilling fungal experiences for humans around the world. Tomorrow, Friday 2/23 from 5-6PM MT, I’ll be helping them kick off their online Sacred Mycology Summit with an interactive session on mycelial community building using the practices of Authentic Relating. The lineup of speakers is amazing, and I’m thrilled to share the stage with some of my mushroom mentors like @mycosymbiote, @tamintegration and @dennismckenna_ as well as emerging leaders like @livefreelaurad @samthemushroomman @4ungi amd @tzutukan. It’s going to be an incredible weekend of learning, connection and mycelial growth! Link in bio to RSVP for free. Don’t miss this!

post_text:
The Future is Fungal 🍄

Fungi fashion? Fungi furniture? Fungi foundations? 🧐

Not only is this attractive alliteration, but it just might be the future of fungi. With its ability to grow rapidly, fit any form, and carry a carbon-neutral footprint, mycelium makes the perfect building material for companies eyeing a more sustainable future. 💫

Mycelium leather has already caught the eyes of industry giants like Adidas, Lululemon, and Stella McCartney. Chairs, canoes, and entire structures have been constructed from fungi. It’s also being used as a replacement for Styrofoam in packaging – eliminating one of the worst environmental pollutants we have. 🙌

Fungi have served as the building blocks for life on Earth for millennia and now we are discovering its immense potential to integrate them to design for our human habitats. The best part is that this is a mutually beneficial relationship for both modern civilization and the natural world. Because mycelium grows agricultural waste the inputs are abundant and dirt cheap, making it an extremely economically viable process. This is only the beginning of the ‘shroom-boom’! 💥

Check out our friends at @soma.eco to discover the latest in mycelial technology! 

Leave a comment below and tell us what products you’d like to see made of mycelium 🍄

post_text:
Este hongo, del género Clavaria, observado en la Quebrada de los Cuervos (Treinta y Tres) por m_coronel94, ¡es nuestra Observación del Mes en NaturalistaUY!
-
Los hongos pertenecen al Reino Fungi y son unos de los seres vivos más diversos de nuestro planeta. Algunos de ellos, como esta Clavaria, se alimentan de la hojarasca y materia orgánica que descomponen en los bosques. Por eso decimos que juegan un rol muy importante en el ciclado de nutrientes de los ecosistemas.

Este grupo de hongos está formado por dos partes: el micelio, que crece en el sustrato, y el cuerpo fructífero, que crece en época reproductiva y normalmente podemos observar a simple vista. En el grupo de las Clavaria en particular, su forma recuerda a los corales, y por ello les llamamos “hongos coraloides”. 

Si bien los hongos crecen durante todo el año, en nuestro país es en otoño cuando encuentran mejores condiciones de humedad y temperatura para fructificar en mayor cantidad. Aún sabemos muy poco de este Reino. De hecho, menos del 20% de las observaciones de hongos logran ser identificadas a nivel de especie en NaturalistaUY.

Para seguir construyendo conocimiento sobre nuestra biodiversidad, ¡sumate vos también a registrar tu entorno! Y si conocés de hongos, ¡ayúdanos con tus identificaciones!
-
Más detalles en https://www.naturalista.uy/observations/213830990
#reinofungi #coralfungi #Clavariaceae #mushroomidentification #mushroomobserver #observaciondelmesnaturalistauy

post_text:
AUSTROPAXILUS SP. -  Graciela Vicente de @recetasysetas nos comparte este ser fascinante, acompañado de una ficha para ayudarnos en la identificación de esta especie. 

Este ejemplar podría tratarse de Austropaxilus statuum, aunque sin estudios adicionales, no podemos asegurar la especie con certeza.

Características:

📸 Ubicación: Chile
⚠️🍽️ Tóxico
🍁 Estación: Otoño
🌿 Hábitat: Bosque nativo
📏 Tamaño: Hongo de tamaño medio, de unos 10-12 cm.
Forma: Similar a una copa con el sombrero algo deprimido en la parte central.
Color: Cutícula suave de color amarillo dorado con descamaciones más oscuras.
Láminas: Muy decurrentes, de color amarillo.
Pie: Corto y amarillo.
Corte: Su carne enrojece al cortarla.
Textura: Fibroso, de olor fenólico y sabor amargo.
Esporada: Parda-amarillenta.

Confusiones Posibles:
Paxilus involutus - Asociado a álamos.
Cantharellus cibarius - Comestible europeo que no se encuentra en Chile.

🍴 Comestibilidad:
Este hongo es tóxico y provoca graves daños gastrointestinales, por lo que se desaconseja su consumo.

Descubre más sobre la diversidad fúngica en nuestra región y aprende a identificar las especies y las mejores recetas fungi con Graciela Vicente.

 ¡Sigamos explorando el fascinante mundo de los hongos!

#reinofungi #setas #hongo #mushroom #nativo #fungi 

¿Ya te encontraste con esta especie? Cuéntanos en comentarios sobre qué otros hongos te gustaría saber más.

post_text:
Glosario para el Antropoceno | Funga

Otoño es temporada de hongos. En esta época es posible observar su estructura macroscópica, que no es más que su cuerpo reproductivo. Es por esta razón que hemos hecho un glosario especial para este reino, tan importante en el engranaje de la vida.

Hasta el siglo pasado, se los consideraba como parte del reino Plantae. Sin embargo, estos se acercan más a los animales que a las plantas, aunque no encajan en ninguno de los dos reinos. Los hongos son la base de la vida, pues construyen los puentes entre todos los ciclos biológicos. Así por ejemplo: son los que contribuyen a hacer el reciclaje de nutrientes en la naturaleza, con sus micorrizas son protagonistas de las asociaciones interespecie y el intercambio de nutrientes, muchos tienen un valor gastronómico relevante y otros, incluso son importantes enteógenos, que nos ayudan a elevar nuestro estado de conciencia. Alimentos, medicinas, transformadores de la materia, mágicos habitantes de los bosques y otros tantos ecosistemas, los hongos merecen su espacio en la clasificación de la biodiversidad. La incorporación del término Funga nos invita, entonces, a apreciar y proteger el mundo de estos seres únicos.

post_text:
🍄🎞️📽️📷 “Las vidas incontroladas de los hongos son un regalo –y una guía– cuando nos falla el mundo controlado que creíamos tener”. Anna Lowenhaupt Tsing, Los hongos del fin del mundo.

Aquí los procesos educativos son espacios de creación lenta. Juntos tratamos de intuir, probar, digerir, girar. A veces no hay avance. Otras el proceso avanza antes que tu propio pensamiento. Antes que tu propia acción. De eso se trata al fin y al cabo. De prestar atención a plena a esos que llamamos otros -hongos, flores, abejas, barro, caliza o talco- y que disponen de estrategias de vida propias de las que poder aprender de y con. 

En este proceso están implicados Darío Fernández, micólogo, junto con Deneb Martos, educadora y artista audiovisual. Ellos, a partir de una estrategia de pensamiento y creación micélica, están actualmente abriendo distintos caminos de experimentación para lograr hacer visible lo invisible, pensando la fotografía de forma expandida y en relación al ecosistema en el que habitamos. 

Haciendo uso de herramientas de la ciencia, la foto sin cámara, el cine experimental, el cultivo y sesiones de campo siguen identificando y comprendiendo especies micológicas de nuestro entorno para poder comprender y visibilizar su papel ecológico.
.
.
.
#micología #mycology #subsuelo #fotosincamara #cineexperimental #reinofungi #tercermaestro

Haciendo uso de herramientas de la ciencia, la foto sin cámara, el cine experimental, el cultivo y sesiones de campo siguen identificando y comprendiendo especies micológicas de nuestro entorno para poder comprender y visibilizar su papel ecológico.
.
.
.
#micología #mycology #subsuelo #fotosincamara #cineexperimental #reinofungi #tercermaestro

post_text:
🍄O passeio que eu tanto sonhei no DF, chegou!!!! Uma trilha Fungi, conhecendo os cogumelos do Cerrado. 🍄 Sempre vi esses passeios de coleta e ensino sobre o Reino Fungi na Europa e EUA e achava legal demais. Agora é possível fazer uma trilha percorrendo nosso bioma e sabendo mais sobre o mundo do cogumelos. Eu experimentei e me amarei na aula do Biólogo Fábio Vieira! Você sabia, por exemplo, que o Cerrado tem dezenas de cogus comestíveis? São os Fungos Alimentícios Não Convencionais. Vi alguns deles no passeio. E alguns medicinais também!!! 

A próxima edição é do fds que vem!!! Coloquei todas as infos no blog! Link na bio e nos stories. 

#reinofungi #cogumelos #brasilia #turismogastronomico #cerradobrasileiro #sustentabilidade #asanorte
IG_auto_desc: Photo by Bárbara Lins on December 04, 2021.

post_text:
🍄🌳Vivência Cogumelos da Mata Atlântica Ed Primavera
Foram muitas trocas e aprendizados ao lado do Jeferson @primaverafungi e deste grupo incrível que se formou para viver esta imersão no @saojoseagroflorestal 

Três dias onde minha família e eu pudemos compartilhar um pouco da história e do trabalho agroflorestal do sítio, além de nos conectarmos com a natureza, explorar trilhas, coletar e estudar o #ReinoFungi. 

🍄Encontramos mais de 90 espécies entre cogumelos e outras formas de fungos, 20 deles com potencial gastronômico e medicinal. Obrigado @marifungi pelas contribuições que engrandeceram a vivência!

🌿As #PANC (plantas alimentícias não convencionais) também tiveram seu espaço, com a super participação da @a.especiarista e levaram todos os participantes para a cozinha. 

Valeu pessoal! 
😍Quem já está querendo mais?

📷Fotos do super @bruno_leao_photo.doc 

#cogumeloscomestiveis #biodiversidadedamataatlantica #cogumelosdamataatlantica #fungi #cogumelos #cogumelossilvestres  #jorgeferreira #jorgeforager #foragerbrasil #primverafungi
IG_auto_desc: Photo by Jorge Ferreira on October 14, 2021.

En Rio Puelo, un hermoso apareció a saludarme en un instante sin lluvia. En ese momento el sol lo bañó.
Dicen que por acá lloverá el viernes. 
Lluvia te espero con este recuerdo.

Crepidotus sp. 
.

post_text:
Nuestro profesor titular e investigador del Centro CiiCC UST, Dr. César Marín, será galardonado con la Medalla Carlos Luis Spegazzini otorgada por la International Mycological Association. Esta condecoración es la más relevante en el estudio investigativo del reino fungi para América Latina. 
La premiación se llevará a cabo en el XII Congreso Micológico Internacional, que se realizará del 11 al 15 de agosto de este año, en la ciudad de Maastricht, Países Bajos.
@micobioma y @fungifest

Conoce más de este gran reconocimiento aquí: https://shorturl.at/mW9w3

#UST #Investigación #micología #hongos #reinofungi

post_text:
ESTRENO‼️ Dinelly Soto nos trajo la tan esperada lluvia a la zona de Pucón y Villarrica.🌧️Junto con la lluvia, nos trajo también super buena onda, anécdotas mega interesantes acerca de hongos que viven a lo largo de todo Chile y también enseñanzas super útiles acerca de cómo comunicar las ciencias y el propio conocimiento.🌱🍄

Tal como nos dijo Dinelly: “si el conocimiento no se comparte, no sirve de nada”. No podemos estar más de acuerdo con esta aseveración.🙌🏽

Les invitamos a emocionarse con este episodio bellísimo acerca de los hongos de Chile, pero también acerca de mucho más que eso: la pasión por aprender continuamente y enseñar con cariño.💚🌳🍄

Muchísimas gracias @dine_cortinaria por estar un ratito con nosotros☺️🍃

Escucha este podcast en Spotify👂🏽🎧

#hongos #fungi #mundofungi #reinofungi
IG_auto_desc: Photo by Volvámonos Verdes® in Chile with @dine_cortinaria.

post_text:
Les damos la bienvenida al Club del Hongo, el programa de membresías del Museo del Hongo! 🍄💫

Desde hace un tiempo, hemos estado trabajando en este proyecto con la visión de crear una comunidad única dedicada a los hongos, donde compartir experiencias, conocimientos e ideas sobre este mundo asombroso.

¿Qué obtendrás al unirte al Club del Hongo?

🌲 Aventuras únicas, con acceso exclusivo a salidas micológicas en la naturaleza.

📚 Material Fungi descargable, que incluye guías, recetas, glosarios y más, diseñados específicamente para los miembros del club.

🧠 Participación en charlas y talleres diseñados en colaboración con personas expertas en diversas áreas.

🍽️ Experiencias gastronómicas explorando la variedad de sabores y texturas de los hongos.

🏛️ Acceso a actividades exclusivas del Museo del Hongo.

💬 Acceso a la comunidad a través del canal de Discord del club, donde podrás interactuar en tiempo real con otras personas amantes por los hongos, compartir tus descubrimientos y mantenerte al tanto de las últimas novedades.

... y muchas sorpresas más que iremos revelando poco a poco.

🍄 Únete al club ingresando en: club.museodelhongo.cl

¡No te quedes fuera de la primera comunidad del FUNGIVERSO! 🌍✨🍄

#clubdelhongo #reinofungi #fungilove #conociendoelfungiverso

.
Siempre quise encontrarme con una especie diferente. Nueva. Que no la hubiera visto antes, ni se la hubiera visto a otros fotógrafos.
Y asi fue. 
El año pasado estábamos sherpa y yo, recorriendo un sendero en carretera austral y una cosita verde diferente llamo mi atención en un tronco. No la habia visto nunca. 
Era un Humidicutis sp 
@giulifungi escribe en su instagram que es una “nueva especie que se encuentra en espera de otra colección para que pueda ser nombrada formalmente en una gran revisión de este grupo”
Sueño cumplido

.

post_text:
Amanita muscaria🍄 es una especie cosmopolita que crece en el sur de Chile🇨🇱, principalmente en la zona de Valdivia y sus alrededores, sin embargo se puede encontrar en casi todas las zonas donde existen predios forestales plantados con pino🌲 radiata.

El único uso documentado para Amanita muscaria corresponde a la utilización en contexto chamanico. Aunque Amanita muscaria es un hongo cosmopolita solo ha sido utilizado en algunas culturas indígenas de Estados Unidos🇺🇸, Rusia 🇷🇺y Mesoamérica.

Actualmente, Amanita muscaria es consumido a baja escala como un alucinógeno 😵‍💫de uso recreativo, en donde no existe un guía o Chaman. Por lo cual resulta en la mayoría de las ocasiones un consumo irresponsable y bastante peligroso. No existe ningún proceso seguro que elimine todas las toxinas en A. muscaria, sin embargo, si se va a consumir se recomienda secarla al sol, pues este proceso disminuye la toxicidad de la muscarina o toxina mata moscas. El secado al sol🌞 también ayuda en la descarboxilación  parcial del ácido iboténico, el cual se transforma en muscimol, sustancia que es aproximadamente 10 veces más alucinógeno. La acción farmacológica del muscimol es diferente de la psilocibina (Psilocibes spp. “Cucumelo”), ya que actúa como agonista del receptor GABAa.

Los riesgos pueden disminuir más si se consume solo la película roja externa del sombrero y la capa que yace inmediatamente por debajo, en el hongo seco. 🛑NUNCA SE DEBE CONSUMIR FRESCO y siempre acompañado de un cuidador o alguna persona que no consuma.

👉Ante todas las recomendaciones pertinentes, siempre es mejor no consumir Amanita muscaria para su uso recreativo. 

🛩️Comparte si te gustó

@vicentevaldesguzmanphotography

post_text:
Holy cow, my “Face Me” portrait article went to print in today’s @arizonadailystar !! What an honor! I love doing these portraits so much 😄. They are in a “blind contour style” which means I don’t look down at the paper while I draw. This leads to hilarity, loss of expectation/control, vulnerability, and connection. You can set up time with me by DMing or popping into my shop, @warm.shape in the @mercadodistricttucson 

I also do a “semi-blind” style of portraiture (slide 2) where I look a little 👀. That style is usually done using photos and not live :) Great for gifts, families, lovers…also could make a great staff t-shirt, just saying!!

I also love doing events! Weddings, birthdays, corporate gigs, I’m open to your ideas! DM “Face Me” to start a conversation :)

Oh yeah and you can also get t-shirts made with the drawings on them. Fun for families, reunions, staff parties, what else??

I ALSO do couples drawing workshops where I guide couples drawing each other, and I’d love to offer one at your business, or a private party! It’s a real hoot! 

The possibilities are endless. I’m right here waiting for your message 😎

(Read the full article for more! Link in bio)

post_text: Explore o mundo dos fungicidas e aprimore seu conhecimento sobre proteção vegetal! 🌿⚔️ Nesta jornada, vamos desvendar os diferentes tipos de fungicidas e seus modos de ação. Desde os protetores, que formam uma barreira preventiva contra infecções fúngicas, até os curativos, que intervêm após a infecção para conter o avanço da doença. E não podemos esquecer dos erradicantes, que entram em ação quando os sintomas já são visíveis, eliminando o inóculo fúngico e restaurando a saúde das plantas. Aprenda como cada tipo de fungicida desempenha um papel crucial na proteção e manejo das doenças fúngicas, garantindo assim a saúde e a produtividade das suas plantas. #Fungicidas #ProteçãoVegetal #Agricultura
IG_auto_desc: Photo by Portal do Agro on May 30, 2024. May be an image of text that says 'Como o Fungicida atua ηα Planta? Os fungicidas são essenciais para proteger e manter α saúde das plantas, controlando e erradicando erro doenças fúngicas. Para uma aplicação eficaz, é crucial entender as diferentes categorias de fungicidas e seus modos de ação. Fungicidas Protetores: Os fungicidas protetores são aplicados preventivamente, criando uma barreira química na superfície da planta que impede α penetração dos esporos fúngicos. Eles são especialmente eficazes quando aplicados antes do início da infecção, proporcionando uma defesa contra α colonização inicial do patógeno. Compartilhando conhecimento Nos siga para mais informações @portal_agro'.

post_text: Explore o mundo dos fungicidas e aprimore seu conhecimento sobre proteção vegetal! 🌿⚔️ Nesta jornada, vamos desvendar os diferentes tipos de fungicidas e seus modos de ação. Desde os protetores, que formam uma barreira preventiva contra infecções fúngicas, até os curativos, que intervêm após a infecção para conter o avanço da doença. E não podemos esquecer dos erradicantes, que entram em ação quando os sintomas já são visíveis, eliminando o inóculo fúngico e restaurando a saúde das plantas. Aprenda como cada tipo de fungicida desempenha um papel crucial na proteção e manejo das doenças fúngicas, garantindo assim a saúde e a produtividade das suas plantas. #Fungicidas #ProteçãoVegetal #Agricultura
IG_auto_desc: Photo by Portal do Agro on May 30, 2024. May be an image of text that says 'Fungicidas Curativos: Fungicidas curativos, também conhecidos como fungicidas sistêmicos ou de pós-infeção, são aplicados após planta já ter sido infectada, mas antes que os sintomas da doença sejam visíveis. Eles penetram nos tecidos da planta e inibem crescimento reprodução do fungo no interior da planta. Fungicidas Erradicantes: Quando os sintomas da infecção fúngica já são visíveis, os fungicidas erradicantes são melhor opção. Esses fungicidas atuam eliminando o inóculo fungico presente na planta, nas sementes ou no solo. São particularmente úteis para manejar doenças estabelecidas e reduzir α de inóculo no ambiente. Compartilhando conhecimento Nos siga para mais informações @portal_agro'.

Fungicida de leche con bicarbonato 

Necesitas: 
200 ml leche 
800 ml agua
20 gr bicarbobato

Preparación:

1. Mezclar en un recipiente la leche con el agua y el bicarbonato 
2. Agitar para que todos los ingredientes se mezclen.
3. Atomizar las plantas cada 2 días siempre el atardecer. El tratamiento es por 15 días mínimo.
4. Se puede usar preventivamente cada 21 días.

A informação nos dá a base para melhor definir o manejo a ser adotado em cada lavoura.

Na imagem conseguimos ver os dados do número de vagens em porcentagem (%) para cada terço da média geral (28 cultivares) e de duas cultivares (Zeus e Titanium). 

Isso significa que o manejo (fungicidas, hormonais, inseticidas…) pode ser específico para cada uma.

Estes dados são médias de 4 repetições casualizadas de cada cultivar com a população indicada do detentor.

Seguimos buscando dados que incrementem ainda mais em nossas recomendações.

post_text:
Os fungicidas sítio-específicos, bem como diz o nome, possuem apenas um local de ação no fungo. Esses locais podem ser a síntese de membrana, ou respiração complexo II, ou respiração complexo III, ou síntese de tubulina do fungo. Ex: Triazóis, estrobilurinas, carboxamidas e benzimidazois.

Nos fungicidas sítio-específicos, o fungo pode sofrer mutação no sítio bioquímico (o sítio-alvo do fungicida), podendo resultar em uma linhagem resistente. Se tal linhagem resistente ocorrer, a aplicação repetida desses fungicidas pode levar ao aumento de uma subpopulação do patógeno resistente.

Multissitios interferem com muitos processos metabólicos de um fungo e são normalmente fungicidas protetores. Uma vez absorvido pela célula do fungo esses fungicidas agem sobre processos como a atividade enzimática que desorganiza numerosas funções celulares. Ex: Mancozebe, Manebe, Tiram, Metiram, Propinebe, Zinebe, Ziram, Clorotalonil, compostos estanhados, sulfúricos, cúpricos, entre outros.

Confira as diferenças entre essas classes de fungicidas nesse post!

#fungicidas #agropos #agro #agroporamor #agronomo #tecnicoagricola

post_text:
Aquele post para salvar📌

Os fungicidas desempenham um papel crucial no manejo dos fungos, responsáveis por aproximadamente 65% das enfermidades que afetam as plantações agrícolas. É fundamental compreender suas categorias para planejar sua aplicação de forma eficaz, prevenindo, por exemplo, o desenvolvimento de resistência a pesticidas.

Podemos utilizar pelo menos 8 critérios distintos para classificar os fungicidas agrícolas, a saber: 

Grupo químico
Principio de controle
Mobilidade
Espectro de ação
Mecanismo de ação
Potencial de periculosidade ambiental 
Toxicologia
Formulações

Quer liberar o seu acesso ao combo de fitopatologia com 52 mapas mentais da matéria?

post_text:
Fungicida casero hecho con leche y bicarbonato, super eficaz para eliminar hongos.

●Como se aplica?
Es de suma importancia que sea al atardecer y luego de los  días de lluvia
Aplicar  durante 2 días seguidos

● Si se hace de forma preventiva, la misma debe ser cada 15 dias aproximadamente.

● Se debe rociar toda la planta por encima y debajo de las hojas

Si el hongo ya está instalado en la planta, hay que quitar todas las hojas mas afectadas y también las que hayan caído a suelo,  Las debemos quemar ...nunca tirar al compost. 

#lahuertaencasa 
#fungicidas
#preparadosnaturales 
#huerta
IG_auto_desc: Photo by La Huerta en Casa 🇦🇷 on January 12, 2021.

post_text:
#Repost @marin_mushrooms:
For #WeeWednesday today, here are some teensy tiny mushrooms, Mycena adscendens, that I found in a small redwood forest in Golden Gate Park some time ago.  The common name for these is Frosty bonnet, and it is easy to see why.  Look at those beautiful sugar-like crystals on the cap!   The larger of these two mushrooms is only about one millimeter tall --  that's quite a bit less than the thickness of a US dime!  The second photo shows these two tiny ones with a slightly more grown up specimen, where you can see the lovely gills.  The last photo is a phone photo (and a very bad one, sorry) showing these mushrooms next to the tip of a ballpoint pen so you can see how really tiny they are.

Image credit: Courtesy of @marin_mushrooms

post_text:
The #Zellers_bolete also known as #Xerocomellus_zelleri) is a solitary mushroom characterised by blackish cap that  appears to shimmer pearlescent under right light. This mushroom's underside is comprised of tightly spaced pores of golden yellow that fade to putrid green with age. It appeara in #coniferous #forests, and also on hardwoods. Its best frature is that It forms symbiotic relationships with tree roots to exchange vital nutrients with its hosts. Fruitbodies will be found popping up from the soil beneath a host tree. However, this is not the case with all its hosts, when it appears beneath redwoods, these trees are not very keen to engage in these symbiotic relationship.

post_text:
Las setas comestibles han sido durante los últimos años uno de los productos más alza en el mundo, esto debido a los cambios de hábito de alimentación que hemos tomado. En la infografía se presentan algunas de las setas chilenas comestibles de origen tanto nativo como endémico, esto con el propósito de conocer más sobre los productos locales que nos entrega nuestro bosque, para que podamos aprovechar de manera sostenible y conocer un poco más de nuestro patrimonio tanto cultural como natural 💚🌳.
(OBS: Las setas 10 y 13 son nativas)

post_text:
Níscalo – Robellón – Callampa rosada
.
El género Lactarius comprende casi 600 especies ectomicorrícicas pertenecientes a la familia Russulaceae. Su mayor característica es la segregación de un látex de color que varía según la especie y que tiene apariencia lechosa, cualidad que le da el epíteto a su género, pues Lactarius proviene del latín “lac” que significa “leche”, siendo el ejemplar probablemente más conocido Lactarius deliciosus.
.
Esta especie se encuentra en plantaciones forestales de Pinus radiata en Chile y su aparición es otoñal e invernal, aunque en ciertas condiciones puede extender incluso hasta verano. Es una seta muy fácil de identificar, a grandes rasgos: tiene una forma de embudo, es quebradizo, con sombrero de color crema a anaranjado, convexo que se aplana con la edad, sobre la superficie del píleo tiene círculos concéntricos; las láminas son adnadas y decurrentes, de color naranjo vivo o zanahoria, al rasgarlas exuda el látex y este se oxida con la presencia de aire dejando un color verdoso; y el pie es cilíndrico, concolor al sombrero, macizo al inicio y luego hueco. 
.
Se trata de una especie muy distintiva por estas características, sin embargo hay otra especie muy parecida en el país: L. quieticolor, que correspondería a la imagen, pues tiene un sombrero mucho más pálido y blanquecino a diferencia de L. deliciosus que tiene el sombrero más anaranjado fuerte y que en apreciación del profesor Gotz es la especie que estaría mayormente en Chile en las plantaciones de pino insigne. 
.
.
Lactarius quieticolor Romagn.
.
.

post_text:
This one goes out to all the BFFs out there (Best Fungi Friends) 💕 besides feeling like a 2 for 1 special when I find them, it warms my lil nerd heart to think of them all getting along, sharing a space and having company 🥲 (I know they could be competitive or parasitic to each other but let's focus on the sharing 😆). First one dedicated to the slimes this #slimemoldsunday 🙌

Likely IDs:
1. Craterium sp. and Diderma sp.
2. Bisporella sp. and Chlorociboria sp.
3. Scutellinia sp. and Dasycyphus sp.
4. Daedaleopsis sp. and Ascocoryne sp.
5. Laetiporus sp. and Ganoderma sp.
6. Russula sp. and Lactarius sp.
7. Sarcoscypha sp. and Mycena sp 
8. Boletus sp. and Lanzia sp.
9. Stereum sp. and Coprinellus sp.
10. Hygrocybe sp. and Mycena sp.

#fantasticfungi #fungifriends #ukfungi #slimemouldsunday #fungi #slime

post_text:
Day 20 #oooplush 
🤍Destroying Angel🤍
(Amanita virosa)

Fastest amatoxin in the west, you mess with them, you’ll be a late-lifeform several days before you even realize it. You’ll be sitting at home, enjoying a good book about mushrooms, and BAM! You've been destroyed and sent to heaven (or to meet Satan's bolete 😈) 

Spooky Fact: Just half a cap can prove lethal to a healthy adult. Fortunately, we’re all children at heart, so….. just don’t eat the Destroying Angel! 

Also I finally found a good craft for those vintage doilies! 

#destroyingangel
#deadlymushroom
#goodandevil
#softactionfigures 
#amanita
#amanitavirosa 
#deadly
#fungifriends 
#knowyourmushrooms
#heavenlymushrooms
IG_auto_desc: Photo by Kami Goertz on October 20, 2021.

Cruentomycena viscidocruenta, commonly known as the ruby bonnet, is a species of agaric fungus in the family Mycenaceae. It is found in moist forested areas of Australia and New Zealand, often in small groups on rotting wood. We have also documented it in India and China.

post_text:
So about last weekend… Better late than never, right?

For the past year and a half I was lucky enough to have a @google mentor and teammate, @chardane. Joining a new company during the pandemic, much less a company which serves billions of people every day, is daunting and overwhelming. More than the “teamsmanship” though, I’m grateful for the friendship and community at work. Work can be more than just a clock in, clock out, paycheck in and out, and I’m glad I was able to experience that with my team.

Sad to see you leave us, but best of luck on your new opportunity @chardane and congrats on the new “senior” title!

post_text: When is $10 not worth $10? That might seem like a ridiculous question, but in fact, $10 can have vastly different values in your head depending on where it comes from and what you’ve decided it’s meant for. For example, you’d probably happily pay $10 for a cocktail if you were on vacation, but tack $10 onto your cell phone bill, and you’d probably complain to customer service. This kind of financial psychology is called mental accounting, and while it’s incredibly common, it can get you into trouble. To learn more, click the link in our bio! #money #spending #budget #fungible #bills #spendingmoney #accounting #psychology #curiosity #finance #finances #financial

post_text:
✨𝗜𝗻 𝘁𝗵𝗲 𝗺𝘆𝘅’✨

Imaginez un organisme à la croisée des règnes animal et végétal, qui se développe comme une plante mais se déplace comme un animal.

 C’est 𝗖𝗲𝗿𝗮𝘁𝗶𝗼𝗺𝘆𝘅𝗮 𝗳𝗿𝘂𝘁𝗶𝗰𝘂𝗹𝗼𝘀𝗮, un myxomycète. 

Il se présente sous une forme étonnante, rappelant un corail miniature ou de minuscules stalactites. 

Ses ramifications blanches se développent sur les bois morts, formant des structures délicates et complexes. Ces ramifications, mesurant jusqu’à 4 millimètres de long, arborent une apparence veloutée due à la présence de spores à leur surface.

Loin d’être statique, Ceratiomyxa fruticulosa suit un cycle de vie semblable aux autres myxomycètes. Tout commence sous forme de spores microscopiques dispersées dans l’air. Lorsqu’elles atterrissent sur un substrat favorable, généralement du bois mort humide, elles germent et se transforment en cellules amiboïdes flagellées dotées d’une capacité de mouvement étonnante puis fusionnent pour former un plasmodium, une masse visqueuse multinucléée. 

Le plasmodium se développe en rampant sur le bois, engloutissant les bactéries et les champignons qui lui servent de nourriture.
Au bout d’un certain temps, le plasmodium se transforme en structures reproductrices appelées sporanges. Ces sporanges libèrent à leur tour de nouvelles spores, perpétuant ainsi le cycle de vie de cet organisme étonnant. 

En décomposant le bois mort, il contribue au recyclage des nutriments dans le sol.

J’imagine que le temps extrêmement pluvieux de cette année favorise son apparition nettement plus remarquée actuellement que d’habitude. 

(Photos en studio 😀)

Ses ramifications blanches se développent sur les bois morts, formant des structures délicates et complexes. Ces ramifications, mesurant jusqu’à 4 millimètres de long, arborent une apparence veloutée due à la présence de spores à leur surface.

Loin d’être statique, Ceratiomyxa fruticulosa suit un cycle de vie semblable aux autres myxomycètes. Tout commence sous forme de spores microscopiques dispersées dans l’air. Lorsqu’elles atterrissent sur un substrat favorable, généralement du bois mort humide, elles germent et se transforment en cellules amiboïdes flagellées dotées d’une capacité de mouvement étonnante puis fusionnent pour former un plasmodium, une masse visqueuse multinucléée. 

Le plasmodium se développe en rampant sur le bois, engloutissant les bactéries et les champignons qui lui servent de nourriture.
Au bout d’un certain temps, le plasmodium se transforme en structures reproductrices appelées sporanges. Ces sporanges libèrent à leur tour de nouvelles spores, perpétuant ainsi le cycle de vie de cet organisme étonnant. 

En décomposant le bois mort, il contribue au recyclage des nutriments dans le sol.

J’imagine que le temps extrêmement pluvieux de cette année favorise son apparition nettement plus remarquée actuellement que d’habitude. 

(Photos en studio 😀)

post_text:
🌿🌿🌿

Serie "Micorriza" Sostenedores de la comunicación.

Mi parte favorita de los hongos es la Simbiosis, esta unión colaborativa con el bosque, la unión con un otro, donde todos son fundamentales, siendo gigante, o muy pequeño. Todos colaboran entre sí. Para mantenerse saludables. 
Porque los hongos son los sostenedores de la comunicación del bosque, del mundo que hay bajo nuestros pies. 
Camina despacio... quizás seas afortunada o afortunado de escuchar lo que pueden decir!

🍄Butyriboletus loyo
🍄Amanita galáctica
🍄Stephanopus azureus 
🍄Cortinarius magellanicus 

Hongos Ectomicorrícicos del territorio llamado Shile.

Impresión en papel texturado
230 grs.
Tamaño postal.

Nos vemos en @festivalfungiconcepcion en 8 y 9 de Junio. 

#yovalgohongo #fantasticfungi #micologia #micorrizas #simbiosis #thinkfungi #fungus #fungilove #print #watercolors #thisischile #hongos #mushrooms

post_text:
Growing a new fungus is always interesting. This is Cordyceps militaris #cordycepsmilitaris a fungi that until recently was not allowed to be grown here in Australia. Now we can legally grow this, I was curious to give it a go - especially after investing so much time into trying to grow Cordyceps gunnii, unsuccessfully!

Not my best grow! And I have been watching lots of US growers really get to dial these in to be an art. But I grew these on white rice with no nutrients to start out so I could get an idea of growth, yield, and other characteristics that may help later! One big hint, don't try to grow these when it is hot without cooling!

post_text:
🎉La Funga Argentina está de fiesta!!! 

🍄Para celebrar el 10° aniversario de Hongos de Argentina queremos compartir el lanzamiento de la 
Guía ilustrada de recolección de hongos

Los hongos son un recurso natural que recibe creciente interés por parte de la sociedad en general. 
El uso de este recurso debe ser racional para asegurar su conservación para generaciones futuras. 
En esta guía compartimos algunos conceptos básicos sobre la biología y ecología de hongos, como también recomendamos métodos para su uso sustentable y cuidado del ambiente.

Link en la bio para poder descargar la Guía ilustrada 🍄

@hongosdeargentina 
@flapjackiestudio 

Las increibles ilustraciones son de @meri.wright

#10añosHongosAr

post_text:
Hace un año que comenzó mi fascinación por el reino Fungi, impresionantes las texturas de estos mágicos seres del bosque. Aquí les enseño mis primeras 10 macro fotografías favoritas tomadas en los bosques valdivianos.
.
1. Amanita muscaria 
2. Amanita muscaria
3. Gliophorus
4. Mycena epipterygia
5. Mycena Haematopus
6. Primordios de armillaria
7. Mycena galericulata 
8. Amanita gayana 
9. cortinarius magellanicus
10. Morchella. ( parque patagonia. Region de Aysen) .
.

A year ago my fascination for the Fungi kingdom began, impressive the textures of these magical beings of the forest.  Here I show you my first 10 favorite macro photographs taken in Valdivian forests.
.
 1. Amanita muscaria
 2. Amanita muscaria
 3. Gliophorus
 4. Mycena epipterygia
 5. Mycena Haematopus
 6. Primordia of armillaria
 7. Mycena galericulata
 8. Amanita gayana
 9. cortinarius magellanicus
 10. Morchella. (patagonia park. Aysen region)
.

post_text:
Coprinellus disseminatus

Estos pequeños hongos, de unos 2 cm de diámetro en el sombrero, suelen aparecer en agrupaciones numerosas sobre madera y cortezas en descomposición, también alrededor de la base de árboles vivos o muertos. 

Los de la foto suelo verlos cada año en el mismo árbol, están ahí varios días hasta que comienza la lluvia y desaparecen. 

#fungi #funga #hongos #thinkfungi #mushrooms #coprinellus #chile #fungachilena #valdivia

post_text:
In 2004 I was cultivating Reishi in Chile, studying from the only books available to me. I saved up, packed the essential, & took off to take @paulstamets course on cultivating gourmet and medicinal mushrooms. He was the author of those books, and the course was taught by him at @fungiperfecti in the PNW. It was incredible! Paul (who was still heavily stammering, btw @fantasticfungi) taught with passion and intense knowledge. This is where I first met somebody who loved fungi as much as I did. A brother. It truly was an awakening for me to understand that it was ok to be mushroom mad like Paul. I learnt to cultivate lion's mane (in the photo), shiitake, oysters, and more. Was taught how to make plug spawn, grain spawn, liquid spawn. I will never forget this transformational trip during my self-learning path in mycology.
If a young woman from Chile did this in the late 90's/early 2000's, you all can do it now!
Shout out to my awesome classmates @bigsilly49 @postcodeman @dameinpack @traddcotter #dontstop #thinkfungi #fungiaretheforce #mushrooms #thefutureisfungi #hongos #mycelium #micelio #rotnmould #rotnmold

post_text:
2018: my 3rd book "Field Guide to Chilean Fungi vol. 2" was published. Honored for the reviews by @janegoodallinst & @paulstamets, and the collaboration of so many fantastic mycologists! 60% of the species described here are native to Chile 🍄❤️ Also, it is the first time all Cyttaria in the Southern Cone are together in a field guide 😎 #thinkfungi #fungiaretheforce

2018: mi 3er libro "Guía de Campo Hongos de Chile vol 2" se publica. Honrada por los comentarios de @janegoodallcl y @paulstamets, y por la colaboración de tantos micólogos y micólogas increíbles! El 60% de las especies son nativas de Chile 🍄❤️. Además, es primera vez que todas las Cyttaria del Cono Sur están juntas en una guía de campo 😎 #yovalgohongo

post_text:
🍄Hongo Sombrero Violeta o Cortinarius Magellanicus 

Se encuentra en el sur de #Chile y #Argentina, y fructifica entre enero y mayo. Es una especie micorrizógena, que crece cerca de árboles principalmente del género Nothofagus. Como se puede ver en la fotografía su color es violáceo con tintes púrpuras.

Este hongo presenta un sombrero de 1 a 8 cm de diámetro. Tanto el sombrero como el estipe están cubiertos de una capa mucilaginosa. La esporada es de color pardo.

post_text:
The brightest spot in the woods, dog vomit slime mold
 (Fuligo septica )
Like many slime molds, the cells of this species typically aggregate to form a plasmodium, a multinucleate mass of undifferentiated cells that may move in an ameboid-like fashion during the search for nutrients. F. septica's plasmodium may be anywhere from white to yellow-gray
This one was so nice and fresh. I was able to do a 20 minute time lapse and compress it down into a few seconds Swipe ➡️to see the pulsating of the slime mold. 
Early mornings are the best time to observe this slime mold. This was spotted on a Ash log, but in urban areas, often found on mulch and wood chip piles. 
.

post_text:
We must not continue down this path of indiscriminate war on microbes. 🔬

The soil microbes, and the beneficial microbes of our body, are the foundation of all life. 

In our misunderstanding and fear of specific microbes, we have launched an all out war on Nature. 

Bacteria, fungi, and viruses are critical to life on Earth. 

Antibiotics, pesticides and fungicides, sanitizers, etc are being used so injudiciously, that the very fabric of human and planetary health is at stake. 

We must learn the patience to discover the difference between friend and foe. 

As with all things in Nature, diversity is the key. Without diversity, the system collapses. 

The invisible microbes do not have a voice of their own - at least not in the traditional sense. But if we continue to ignore them, the microbial ecosystem will become so imbalanced that we will be forced to pay attention to their power. 

There is no life in a fully sterilized world. 

We must learn to live alongside these microbes, and acknowledge the significant role they play in the health of our planet. 

#microbes #invisible #tiny #microscopic #soilorganisms #organism #life #earth #motherearth #ecosystem #circleoflife #systemsthinking #systems #fungicides #pesticides

post_text:
You might have read our recent post about the excessive use of damaging pesticides in imported cut flowers, but of almost equal concern is fungicide usage.  You see, Ecuador, where many of the roses sold in the US are grown, has high amounts of rainfall and the greenhouses where these flowers are grown are notorious for holding in humidity and creating fungus issues like Botrytis. Botrytis can create spots on a rose, and often won't appear on a rose until after it's left the farm. 

To prevent these spots from showing up on roses once they hit the retail market and dissuading customers from buying them, foreign growers have developed a worrisome and toxic method of dipping the entire rose into a vat of fungicide, first dunking the bloom, and then the stem.  The workers in charge of this job wear respirator masks to avoid inhaling the products, which are then packaged directly into flower sleeves and shipped to the US (no, they are not rinsed off afterward). Of the 37 products that are used as rose dip treatments, 17 of them have been identified by the Pesticide Action Network to be problematic as groundwater pollutants or harmful to humans, toxic to life and the environment. 
Unfortunately, Valentine's Day, the biggest flower holiday in the US, is also a time when domestic roses are, by and large, dormant in their fields. This means the VAST majority of cut roses purchased during February have been dipped in a toxic blend of fungicides and pesticides. Not exactly the way I'd want to say "I love you!"

BREAKING: Toxin Free USA has filed a consumer protection lawsuit against Target for deceptive marketing of their Good and Gather "All Natural" Raisins after independent lab tests detected 11 different pesticides in a single sample. Target markets these raisins to children, with a version of packaging that contains a cartoon giraffe. Parents, grandparents and other caregivers need to know! 😡

“As a mother, I’m appalled and saddened that Target chooses to mislead shoppers and puts our children at risk of consuming toxic pesticides. Big corporations like Target have the ability and buying power to make our food system safer and healthier and still turn a good profit, yet they choose to deceive instead. Americans are demanding better and it’s time for Target to deliver. We hope this lawsuit will stop their deception and nudge them in the right direction,” says Diana Reeves, executive director of Toxin Free USA.
Click on the linktree link in our bio near the top of our home page to read the full press release and the complaint.

GMO Free USA has now filed our second Consumer Protection lawsuit on behalf of U.S. consumers. We need your help to increase the pressure on the Panera Bread restaurant chain. Call 855-372-6372 – tell them to COME CLEAN and stop the misleading marketing!

Why did we sue Panera Bread? On the heels of our report on restaurant food testing, Eating Out: A Date with Glyphosate, we announced the filing of a consumer protection lawsuit against Panera. We were shocked that the restaurant food test results found certain foods from Panera had the highest glyphosate residues of all 15 restaurants chains tested. That’s right, higher levels than junk foods tested from McDonald’s, Taco Bell, Subway, Dunkin' Donuts and Domino’s Pizza to name a few. Panera’s whole grain bagel contained 677 ppb glyphosate, compared to a bagel from Dunkin’ Donuts that tested at 353 ppb. And Panera prides itself on the marketing claim that “100% of our food is 100% clean.” That’s not clean, Panera! A reasonable consumer expects “clean food” to be free of contaminants, including toxic pesticides like glyphosate and agricultural fungicides.

Panera’s marketing campaign exploits consumers’ preferences for truly clean food, misleading us to believe that Panera foods are better quality than other restaurants. That makes our blood boil. And it should make yours boil too! Junk food restaurants like McDonald’s don’t go to lengths to deceive us about the true quality of their food. Panera benefits financially from this misleading advertising and should be held accountable. That’s why we're suing Panera Bread. Read more - links in bio!

But we need your help to keep the pressure on Panera. Call and tell them that it's NOT OK to advertise food that contains toxic synthetic pesticides as "Clean Food" 855-372-6372. And please donate to help us ramp up our Clean Up Restaurant Food Campaign and hold these corporations accountable! #PaneraBread #Panera #restaurants #food #glyphosate #weedkiller #carcinogen #WholeGrainBagel #bagels #ADateWithGlyphosate #lawsuit #ConsumerProtection #CleanFood #pesticides #fungicides #herbicides #CleanLabelProject #gmofreecanada #gmofreeusa

post_text:
✅This is a great example of what happens to a crop when it is not sprayed. 

🚜The picture shows what happens when a spray miss occurs. 

🌾The noticeable yellowing indicates the crop’s deterioration due to diseases such as yellow rust.

Why is this a problem ? 

☀️ The process of photosynthesis, which is vital for the plant’s growth, relies on the absorption of light into the plant’s green leaves. When these leaves are afflicted by disease, the amount of photosynthetically active radiation (PAR) they can absorb is significantly reduced. This leads to a decrease in photosynthesis, ultimately resulting in a lower yield.

❌This could have occured  due to a blocked nozzle.

post_text:
Credit :@mushroom.millah🤍

Hello, hi, I'm still here. Just unintentionally took a 5 week break from posting, it seems. Now that I'm working full time, I haven't been wanting to even turn my computer on at weekends. I've been out in the forest, taking photos, reading, dating, caring for my plants, learning to drive... just not spending much time editing my photos. We haven't had any rain here in a month so there's also a distinct lack of fungi around right now. 

Anyway, here's throwing it back to peak mushroom season in Sandringham's arboretum.

Amanita muscaria, Fly Agaric 
Norfolk, Oct '22

post_text: I always love finding Mycena acicular, commonly known as the orange bonnet or the coral spring Mycena. They are so colourful but so incredibly tiny to find. I usually find them after I'm parked on the ground taking photos of another larger fungi find. The larger one in the photo was about 1cm tall. Found these a couple days ago.

(Daldinia concentrica / King Alfred’s Cakes)

post_text:
Questa è l'#Irlanda nella sua veste migliore: oceano blu e dolci colline verdi. La penisola di #Dingle è stata definita una volta da @natgeo “Il luogo più bello sulla Terra”. Dopotutto, fu conquistata dai #Vichinghi, ha accolto le star di Hollywood provenienti da una Galassia lontana lontana, e il suo abitante più famoso è un delfino.

Proprio cosí, un #delfino, #Fungie. Ormai è praticamente parte della famiglia. Fin dal 1983, questo simpatico amico ha divertito chiunque abbia visitato la costa di Dingle.

E tu, sei mai stato nella penisola di Dingle?

#loveIreland #turismoirlanda #itinerari #irishfacts #scopriirlanda #visitireland #visitdingle #vacanzainirlanda
IG_auto_desc: Photo by Turismo Irlanda in Dingle, Ireland.

post_text:
Photos by @Justin.Jin / Fungie, a dolphin that has made Dingle a world-famous tourist destination since the day he befriended a local fisherman 37 years ago, has not been seen near the Irish harbor town for weeks. Many people around the world are mourning the bottlenose dolphin that has chosen humans as his lifelong friends.
I set out to sea to photograph Fungie in 2006. For days he was nowhere to be seen, and suddenly he leapt out of the water right next to my boat. It was challenging to capture the moment because I didn't know where he might appear and when. I jumped into the frigid water to swim with him, but he did not oblige. Our brief encounters touched me. I can understand the people in Dingle missing him dearly. Goodbye, Fungie.
Follow photographer @Justin.Jin for more stories and pictures from around the world. #dingle #dinglepeninsula #swimfreefungie #fungie #fungiethedolphin
IG_auto_desc: Photo by National Geographic Travel on October 30, 2020.

Page One Photo: Fungie, the famous Dingle dolphin, is lonely for human contact according to those closest to him. Leisure tours are banned due to Covid-19 restrictions. post_text:
A critically endangered fungus - Tea-tree Fingers.

This colony was only recently discovered by colleagues and is bigger than all the other previously known fruiting bodies combined. And it's the only colony within a National Park.

The whacky thing is it feeds on another couple of specific species of fungi, so to conserve this fungus, we must conserve its hosts first.

The other colonies are threatened by sand mining activity.

#teatreefingers
#rememberthewild #wildvictoria #VicOurNature #fungimap #endangered #SaveWesternportWoodlands

post_text:
Photos by @Justin.Jin / Fungie, a dolphin that has made Dingle a world-famous tourist destination since the day he befriended a local fisherman 37 years ago, has not been seen near the Irish harbor town for weeks. Many people around the world are mourning the bottlenose dolphin that has chosen humans as his lifelong friends.
I set out to sea to photograph Fungie in 2006. For days he was nowhere to be seen, and suddenly he leapt out of the water right next to my boat. It was challenging to capture the moment because I didn't know where he might appear and when. I jumped into the frigid water to swim with him, but he did not oblige. Our brief encounters touched me. I can understand the people in Dingle missing him dearly. Goodbye, Fungie.
Follow photographer @Justin.Jin for more stories and pictures from around the world. #dingle #dinglepeninsula #swimfreefungie #fungie #fungiethedolphin
IG_auto_desc: Photo by National Geographic Travel on October 30, 2020.
